character of the characters, and (5) ) teachers and 
students need learning media for writing 
narrative texts that are able to improve language 
competence, develop creativity, and foster good 
character in students.

  
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
Picture 1.   The Prototype of Folklore-Based Serial 
Image Media 
 
Based on this exploratory study, a prototype 
of folklore-based serial image media was 
developed for learning to write narrative texts. 
The development of folklore-based serial image 
media is carried out through the following stages: 
(1) preparing a prototype of folklore-based serial 
image media, (2) developing a folklore-based 
serial image media prototype, then validated by 
2 experts, namely learning media experts and 
learning material experts, (3) implementing 
folklore-based serial image media products at 
the research location, and (4) assessing the 
feasibility of folklore-based serial image media 
by potential users, namely teachers and research 
subject students.  
Folklore-based serial image media was 
developed in the form of a book measuring 25 x 
18 centimeters, which consists of several parts,  
as follows: (1) The front cover contains a picture 
of three students writing, with a title “Ayo 
Menulis Cerita Rakyat”, name of the media 
composer; (2) Contents contain a series of serial 
images with folklore themes. There are six 
media, each containing folklore originating from 
the Madiun City area and its surroundings, 
namely: (a) “Rara Maris yang Malang”, (b) 
Terjadinya Telaga Ngebel”, (c) “Joko Damar”, 
(d) “Asal-Usul Nama Madiun”, (e) “Ki Ageng 
Mirah”, and (f) “Asal Usul Reog Ponorogo”; (3) 
The back cover contains writing about the 
benefits of writing narrative texts for students 
and a description of the values contained in 
folklore and the importance of the existence of 
folklore as the nation's noble heritage. 
Each media is equipped with instructions 
for using the media and instructions for writing 
narrative text assignments. It is also equipped 
with character descriptions to make it easier for 
students to understand the folklore contained in 
serial image media. Each serial image media 
consists of 8 images, which are arranged 
sequentially to form a complete story plot. The 
steps for the activity of writing narrative text 
based on folklore-based serial image media are 
explained as follows: (1) the teacher explains the 
nature of narrative text and techniques for 
writing narrative text; (2) students observe the 
serial image media and identify the existing 
characters; (3) the teacher briefly tells the 
folklore according to the series of existing 
pictures; (4) the teacher gives students the 
opportunity to ask questions about things that are 
considered 
unclear; 
(5) 
using 
their 
own 
sentences, students write narrative text referring 
to the series of pictures in the media; (6) students 
identify 
the 
moral 
values 
and 
messages 
contained in the folklore they write; (7) students 
read the narrative text they wrote in front of their 
friends to get responses from other students and 
the teacher. 
 
Validation Results of the Prototype of 
Folklore-Based Serial Image Media 
The prototype of folklore-based serial 
image media that has been prepared is then 
consulted with experts. Expert assessment is 
carried out with the aim that the media 
developed has substantive truth and its quality 
can be accounted for from a scientific 
perspective. This expert assessment activity is 
carried out before the learning media prototype 
is tested. The results of assessments, discussions, 
and input from experts are used as a reference 
for making improvements to the media being 
developed. Two experts were selected to carry 
out the assessment, namely a language learning 
materials expert and a learning media expert. 
The expert assessment instruments each 
contain 10 items. Language learning material 
experts and learning media experts provide 
assessments and suggestions for folklore-based 
serial image media. Suggestions given by 
language learning material experts, namely: (1) 
at the beginning, the learning objectives and 
competencies to be achieved must be explained;

 
 
(2) instructions for using learning media must be 
prepared in clear sentences so that they are 
easily understood by users; (3) the task of 
creating narrative texts should be equipped with 
indicators of competency achievement related to 
linguistic aspects; (4) the results of student 
writing must be discussed analytically and 
holistically by teachers and students; and (5) 
learning folklore must shape character and 
enrich students' cultural insight. Apart from 
providing input, language learning material 
experts also provide assessments about the 
quality of folklore-based serial image media, as 
shown in Table 2 below.  
 
