Discussion 
 
The development of folklore-based serial 
image media for learning to write narrative texts 
is based on an analysis of the conditions for 
learning to write narrative texts in elementary 
schools in the Madiun City area. The results of 
the research show that learning to write narrative 
texts is teacher-centered, most teachers do not 
use learning media that can increase students' 
writing motivation, and most students do not 
understand the nature of narrative texts, have 
poor vocabulary, sentence structures are not well 
structured, story plots are difficult to understand, 
and are unable to elaborate on the character's 
character. The problem of difficulty in writing 
narrative text is in accordance with the research 
results  Telaumbanua (2020), which explains 
that students face three types of challenges when 
creating narrative texts: cognitive, linguistic, and 
psychological challenges. Prihandani's research 
(2023) revealed that there were errors due to 
interlingual and intralingual transfers made by 
students in writing narrative texts. Apart from 
that, there are also cognitive aspects that make 
students find it difficult to write narrative texts 
due to a lack of knowledge of grammar and 
vocabulary. 
Research by Emilsa & Guslinda (2019) and  
Perdiana & Suryadi (2022) found almost the 
same results, namely that students' narrative 
writing ability scores were relatively low. There 
are several factors that cause school students' 
low ability to write narrative texts. basic, 
including 
that 
because 
are 
less 
interested and feel bored with writing material, 
they have difficulty choosing words and using 
spelling. Students' vocabulary is limited, so the 
words used in writing are limited to words that 
are repeated. Students are less skilled in 
connecting one sentence to another, so a good 
paragraph is not formed. Students do not have 
good knowledge of how to place punctuation 
marks. The research results of Wibowo et al. 
(2020) 
revealed 
that 
were 
less 
enthusiastic and lazy when writing narrative 
texts; students still had difficulty choosing words 
to express the ideas in their minds; and the 
content of the story was not continuous from 
beginning to end.   
The development of folklore-based serial 
image media is based on the needs of teachers 
and students for media that can attract students' 
interest in writing and, at the same time, improve 
students' narrative text writing skills. Media was 
developed using the ADDIE prototype (Analysis, 
Design, 
Development, 
Implementation,

 
 
Evaluation) 
(Mulyatiningsih, 
2012). 
The 
folklore-based serial image media prototype 
consists of 3 parts, namely the front cover, 
contents, and back cover. The contents section 
contains a series of pictures with six folk tales, 
and each folk tale title contains a series of eight 
pictures. This section is also equipped with 
instructions for using media, instructions for 
writing narrative text assignments, and character 
descriptions to make it easier for students to 
write narrative texts according to the title of 
folklore. 
The media design developed was then 
validated by two experts, namely a media expert 
and a language learning expert. The purpose of 
this 
validation 
is 
to 
obtain 
advice 
and 
assessments from experts regarding the learning 
media being developed. The revised learning 
media, based on input from experts, was then 
implemented in three elementary schools. 
Following the trial, a quality and feasibility 
assessment of folklore-based serial picture media 
was conducted by educators and students. 
Based on the trial results, it is known that 
the serial image media based on folklore is 
declared to be very good and suitable for 
application in learning to write narrative texts for 
sixth 
grade 
elementary 
school 
students. 
Specifically, it was also found that there was an 
increase in narrative text writing skills after the 
implementation of folklore-based serial image 
media. This can be seen in several indicators, 
including an increase in students' vocabulary, 
more structured sentences, varied paragraphs, 
and better use of spelling. One thing that still 
needs attention is the aspect of how to structure 
the 
storyline 
and portray the 
characters' 
characters, which has not been well developed. 
This is understandable because developing good 
narrative text writing skills requires long-term 
practice. The development of students' writing 
skills needs to always be improved and trained 
continuously (Cattoni et al., 2024; Hamid & 
Jahan, 2023). Writing is a very complicated act 
because it contains a consistent perspective and 
different things related to the method of 
composing, for example: (1) unity of thought; (2) 
use of clear and strong sentences; (3) orderly 
arrangement of paragraphs; (4) use of correct 
spelling rules; and (5) sufficient vocabulary 
dominance (Slamet et al., 2014). Writing is a 
recursive interaction, and it implies students 
overhaul the entire cycle, often changing to and 
from between stages (Urquhart & Monette, 
2005).  
The results of the research show that 
folklore-based serial image media is effectively 
applied to learning to write narrative texts for 
elementary school students. This media has been 
proven to be able to attract students' interest, 
making it easy for students to develop their 
writing ideas based on the series of images 
available. This is in line with the opinion of 
Hidayah et al. (2020) which states that serial 
image media makes it easier for students to write 
narrative texts. This media is considered the 
right solution to generate new desires and 
interests, motivation, learning stimulation, and 
even a psychological influence on children's 
learning (John & Bates, 2023). Serial image 
media plays a role in learning to write because it 
can help students gain concepts about a 
particular topic by observing serial images and 
then putting them into written form. 
Many related studies corroborate the results 
of this investigation. Research by Dalle et al. 
(2020) stated that serial image media has a 
positive effect on elementary school students' 
writing skills. Serial image media has been 
proven to help students develop and memorize 
various ideas in written form. Lestari's research 
(2021) carried out in Cipinang, Jakarta, also 
showed the same results. The results of 
measurements before the research showed that 
more than 50% of students had low abilities in 
writing narrative texts, especially in the use of 
spelling, composing sentences, developing ideas, 
vocabulary, and interest in writing. After 
conducting experiments, it was proven that the 
use of serial image media had a positive effect 
on elementary school students' ability to write 
narrative texts. The use of serial image media 
can provide new innovations for teachers in 
learning and encourage students to practice 
actively and develop their imagination in writing 
narrative texts. Through a series of images, 
students will think logically about cause-and-
effect relationships relating one image to another. 
The theme used in writing narrative text 
through a series of image media is folklore 
originating from the Madiun City area and its 
surroundings. The choice of folklore themes is 
seen to attract students' interest because folklore 
contains various messages and aims to provide 
advice and also to entertain (Ismail et al., 2015). 
Every folklore has character strengths that

  
reflect the behavior of previous people, settings, 
and storylines that are influenced by the 
environment the story originates from. Students 
can learn about good values through the 
messages implicit in folklore (Normaliza, 2014). 
Miller (2013) revealed that folklore has a big 
impact on the growth of the younger generation 
in understanding the good values of their 
ancestors. The character formation of students at 
school is not only obtained through subjects but 
also through folklore, for example, by reading 
and writing folklore (Nadeak et al., 2020). 
Utilizing folklore as an alternative learning 
material can make it a more effective means of 
teaching morals, teaching culture, broadening 
horizons, and motivating students.   
Folklore, as Indonesia's cultural heritage 
presents various kinds of societal characters, is 
appropriate to use as a vehicle for forming 
student character and personality. Folklore 
contributes to children's education, learning, 
reflective 
thinking, 
concept 
formation, 
imagination, and social interaction (Agbenyega 
et al., 2017). In learning folklore, teachers can 
use various media, such as a series of pictures 
and puppets. Teachers can describe various 
characters so that students can learn about good 
and bad characters and various moral values 
through folklore (Nanda et al., 2021; Rolina, 
2015). Folklore is not only used to convey 
messages, ideas, and values but can also be used 
to understand information, store it, and pass on 
generation. Before using folklore as learning 
matFolklore is not only used to convey messages, 
ideas, and values but can also be used to 
understand information, store it, and pass on 
geneFolklore is not only used to convey 
messages, ideas, and values but can also be used 
to understand information, store it, and pass on 
generation. Before using folklore as learning 
material, teachers must consider the positive and 
negative effects on students.  
The folklore chosen should contain moral 
values, which students can use to distinguish 
between good and evil characters (Santosa et al., 
2023). The folklore chosen as learning material 
is endeavored to be well known and come from 
life around the students because the storyline, 
language, and traditions present in folklore often 
have close ties to their owners and even reflect 
the personalities of the people. The role of 
characters in folktales is important because they 
can help future generations learn from the stories 
by examining the setting, timeline, and moral 
implications as part of academic research 
(Macfarlane, 2020) and also for the study of 
folklore (Vovk, 2017). Kusnita's research (2020) 
asserts that teaching folklore in schools is 
necessary to prevent alien cultures that have 
influenced education through technological 
advancements from displacing the values found 
in it.  
 
CONCLUSIONS 
 
Based on the research results and discussion, 
the conclusions of this research are formulated 
as follows. Based on exploratory studies, it is 
known that. Learning to write narrative texts is 
teacher-centered, most teachers do not use 
learning media that can increase students' 
writing motivation, and students' ability to write 
narrative texts is still low. This is reflected in 
students' lack of understanding of the nature of 
narrative texts, poor vocabulary, sentence 
structures that are not well structured, story plots 
that are difficult to understand, and their 
inability 
to 
elaborate 
on 
the 
characters' 
characters. The results of the exploratory study 
also revealed that teachers and students need 
learning media for writing narrative texts that are 
able to improve language competence, develop 
creativity, and foster good character in students. 
Furthermore, based on this exploratory 
study, a prototype of folklore-based serial image 
media was created in book form, which 
contained a series of serial images with six folk 
tales. The prototype was then assessed by two 
experts, namely an expert in the field of 
language learning and a learning media expert. 
The input and results of expert assessments are 
used to make improvements to the prototype so 
that the learning media prepared is declared 
suitable for testing on research subjects.  
The trial results showed an increase in 
narrative 
text 
writing 
skills 
after 
the 
implementation of folklore-based serial image 
media. This can be seen in the increase in 
students' vocabulary, more structured sentences, 
varied paragraphs, and better use of spelling. 
Based on the trial results, it is known that the 
serial image media based on folklore is declared 
to be very good and suitable for application in

 
 
learning to write narrative texts for sixth grade 
elementary school students.  
It is recommended for elementary school 
teachers outside the Madiun City area to learn to 
write narrative texts using a series of image 
media with folklore themes originating from 
their respective regions. It is hoped that the 
results of this research will inspire other 
researchers to develop learning media and 
learning models for writing narrative texts that 
are innovative and suit the needs of elementary 
school students.","This study aims to describe the development of folklore-based serial image media in learning to write narrative texts for elementary school students. This research uses a development research approach using ADDIE (analysis, design, development, implementation, evaluation). Exploratory studies were conducted in 10 elementary schools and trials were conducted in 3 elementary schools in the Madiun City area. Data collection in exploratory studies used observation, interviews, and documents, while questionnaires were used to obtain input and assessment from experts, teachers, and students. Data analysis techniques use descriptive analysis. The results showed that folklore-based serial image media is feasible to be used in learning to write narrative texts for elementary school students. Folklore-based serial image media has also proven effective in improving students' narrative text skills."
"MISREPRESENTATION OF THE INDONESIAN ULEMA COUNCIL 
IN FATWAS ON SHI'A: NORMAN FAIRCLOUGH MODEL OF 
CRITICAL DISCOURSE ANALYSIS 
Muhammad Ridwan, Arifuddin, Eva Varhah, Muhammad Yunus Anis, Reza Sukma Nugraha, 
Afnan Arummi, Tri Yanti Nurul Hidayati, Khabibi Muhammad Luthfi 
1,,2,3,4,5,6,7,8 Program Studi Sastra Arab, Fakultas Ilmu Budaya, Universitas Sebelas Maret 
1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8 Jl. Ir. Sutami No.36, Surakarta, Jawa Tengah  
 
Article History:  
Submitted: 6 June 2024; Revised: 15 June 2024, Accepted: 2 July 2024 
 
 
RETORIKA: Jurnal Bahasa, Sastra dan Pengajarannya under 
