Abstract: This writing aims to synthesize the misrepresentation strategy presented by the MUI in 
its fatwa on Shia. This writing is a descriptive qualitative type with a critical paradigm approach. 
The data sources for this writing are the Central Indonesian Ulema Council's 1984 Fatwa on Shia 
Beliefs and the 2012 East Java Provincial Indonesian Ulema Council's Fatwa on the Deviance of 
Shia Teachings. The research data consists of the vocabulary and grammar utilized and selected by 
the MUI in the fatwa on Shia. This issue is examined through Norman Fairclough's critical 
discourse analysis, including the experiential value and relational value of vocabulary and 
grammar. The results of this research show that the MUI, in its fatwa on Shia, displays and 
orchestrates with an excommunication approach. The fatwa succeeds in expressing the practice of 
domination by the fatwa producers over the followers of Shia beliefs. The fatwa successfully 
becomes a discourse that holds power. This is represented through linguistic units referenced to 
Shia beliefs. The MUI chooses and supports Sunni beliefs while marginalizing Shia beliefs. The 
representation of the linguistic units utilized by the MUI presents Shia beliefs as incorrect while 
portraying Sunni beliefs as correct. This shows the presence of misrepresentation or incorrect 
depiction by the text producers. This strategy is called a misrepresentation strategy. The model of 
misrepresentation employed by the MUI includes marginalization, delegitimization, and 
exclusivity. 
 
Keywords: fatwa Shi'a, critical discourse analysis, ideology 
 
Sectarian rhetoric that dehumanizes ""the 
other"" dates back centuries (Siegel, 2015; Siegel 
& Badan, 2020). This rhetoric is realized 
through hateful speech, especially anti-Shi'a 
hatred (Rohmad, 2019). Empirical studies and 
journalistic reports show that the escalation of 
violations of religious freedom and intolerance 
of Shi'a (Akmaliah, 2015). The pursuit of anti-
Shi'a hatred is increasing with the tone of 
""heretical misleading, wicked, infidel, apostate, 
haram, deviating from the Islamic creed, and out 
of Islam"" (Ahmad et al, 2019). In fact, hate 
speech is increasingly being heard to the public. 
Articulation by highlighting the differences 
between the two understandings is always 
highlighted by the state apparatus and non-state 
apparatus. This prominence results in the birth of

 
 
sectarian friction (Ahmad, 2019; Akmaliyah, 
2015). 
The popularization of anti-Shi'a sectarian 
rhetoric in Indonesia is referred to and based on 
several legal products made by, both state and 
non-state apparatus. The state apparatus has 
issued three regulations, namely (1) Decree of 
the President of the Republic of Indonesia 
Number 
1/PNPS 
of 
concerning 
""Prevention of Abuse and/or Blasphemy"" dated 
January 27, 1965, (2) Circular Letter of the 
Ministry 
of 
Religious 
Affairs 
Number 
D/BA.01/4865/1983, dated December 5, 1983 
concerning ""Matters concerning Shi'a Groups"", 
and (3) East Java Governor Regulation Number 
55 of 2012 concerning ""Development of 
Religious Activities and Supervision of Cults in 
East Java dated July 23, 2012 (Fadhilla, 2013). 
Then, legal products produced by the 
Indonesian Ulema Council suppressed Shi'a in 
organization and teachings believed by followers 
of Shi'a. Legal products related to this 
understanding include the fatwa of the Central 
MUI in 1984 concerning Shi'a and the fatwa of 
the MUI of East Java Province in 2012 
concerning the Heresy of Shi'a Teachings. 
Furthermore, legal products related to Shi'a 
teachings include the Central MUI fatwa on 
Mut'ah Marriage in 1997, the Central MUI fatwa 
on the Law of Insulting and Disbelieving the 
Companions of the Prophet Muhammad in 2016, 
the Central MUI fatwa in 2017 concerning the 
Law of Doubting the Perfection of the Qur'an, 
and the Central MUI fatwa on Believing in the 
Infallibility of Imams ('Ishmatul Imam) (Team of 
the Directorate General of Bimas of the 
Indonesian Ministry of Religious Affairs, 2011). 
The emergence of several questions about 
Shi'a understanding above can play an important 
role in mobilizing inter-sectarian conflicts, 
namely Sunni and Shi'a (Miswanto, 2021). 
Although this legal product is only one of many 
factors that play a role in driving conflict 
between the two ideas, it plays a very strong role 
and increases feelings of hatred in the wider 
community.  
Text producers realize that this legal 
product is important to be issued to detect and 
predict political instability, violence, and even 
genocide (Puslibang Team for Religious Life, 
2021). In general, the legal product of Shi'ism is 
an extreme form of rhetoric violating religious 
freedom and tolerance. This legal product can be 
considered very dangerous for the continuity of 
relations between Shi'a and Sunni (Fathilla, et al, 
2022). The relationship between these two ideas 
is further muddied by the emergence of 
sectarianism. 
Sectarianism is a pro-group bias based on 
affiliation with a certain religious group or 
religion (Alnizar, 2019; Alnizar et al, 2021). 
Favoritism within groups and a preference for 
one's own ideology or school are key aspects of 
sectarian ownership and identification. Thus, 
sectarianism 
involves 
the 
of 
identification 
with a particular 
group of 
confessions, or the categorization of oneself and 
others 
based 
on 
sectarian 
lines. 
identification relates to other anti-group attitudes 
and behaviors, especially when the distinction 
between 
groups 
is 
based 
on 
ideological 
orientation and sociological aspects (Weisel & 
Böhm, 2015). Identification with a group (Shi'a 
understanding by Sunnis) causes individuals to 
form an ""we are their opponent"" mentality 
(Wakefield, 2017). This mentality is able to 
increase attitudes and behaviors with nuances of 
hatred. 
The presence of the text of the Central MUI 
fatwa on ""Shi'ah Understanding"" in 1984 and the 
MUI Fatwa of East Java Province on ""Shi'ah 
Teachings"" in 2012 was made by the superior 
group or ingroup or inclusive or Sunni or Ahlus 
Sunnah wal Jama'ah group to consider Shi'ah 
understanding to be in an outgroup or inferior or 
exclusive position. This implies and represents 
that fatwa as a discourse is used as a stepping 
stone for violations of religious freedom and 
tolerance (Hoffman, 2019; Menchik, 2016). 
The discourse of fatwa related to Shi'a 
understanding is like a living creature that is able 
to persuade and exercise its authority (Makin, 
2017). Exclusivism gives rise to acts of 
intolerance and even violence against followers 
of Shi'ism. With this, who is in grouping and 
who is out of grouping can be understood 
(Albadi et al, 2018). 
Research on anti-Shia movements covers a 
wide range of disciplines such as religious 
studies, 
political 
science, 
sociology, 
and 
anthropology. The research is based on several 
approaches. First, paradigma historicism among 
others, 
Formichi 
(2014); 
Siegel 
(2020); 
Akmaliyah (2015). This first group examines the 
history of differences and conflicts between 
Sunnis and Shiites from the early days of Islam

  
to the present day and the development of anti-
Shia movements in various historical periods, 
including 
the 
influence 
of 
colonialism, 
nationalism, and modern politics. 
Second, the study of anti-Shi'ah movements 
with phenomenological paradigms includes 
Hoffman (2019). This second group discusses 
the political, social, and economic dynamics that 
affect the emergence and development of anti-
Shia movements and the role of states, political 
groups, 
and 
community 
organizations 
in 
supporting or opposing these movements. 
Third, 
the 
study 
of 
the 
anti-Shi'ah 
movement with a hermeneutic paradigm by 
Hakim (2021) which identifies the demographic 
and social characteristics of the perpetrators of 
the anti-Shia movement and understands the 
perception and attitude of the general public 
towards the Shia community and the anti-Shia 
movement. 
Fourth, the study of the anti-Shi'ah 
movement with a critical paradigm, among 
others, by Formichi (2014); Menchik (2016). 
This fourth group examinesthe role of mass 
media, social media, and religious literature used 
to spread anti-Shia ideology and studiesthe 
rhetoric and narratives used in anti-Shia 
campaigns. 
This research focuses on the fatwa texts 
issued by the Central MUI in 1984 regarding the 
""Shi'ite Understanding"" and the fatwa issued by 
the East Java Provincial MUI in 2012 regarding 
the ""Deviation of Shi'ite Teachings."" The 
problem statements related to this focus are (1) 
how is the marginalization strategy utilized by 
the MUI? (2) how is the delegitimization 
strategy presented by the MUI? (3) how is the 
exclusivity strategy pursued by the MUI? 
Language and power are two entities that 
have a systemic and systematic attachment and 
closeness. The identity of the speaker of the 
language or the authority of the speaker of the 
language and the choice of style and diction 
contain power and influence in perpetuating the 
dominance of power (Maisaroh et al., 2023). 
Speakers or producers of texts produce specific 
linguistic units to identify, define, categorize, 
and position Shi'ism. This orchestration is an 
effort by text producers to contest and fight for 
the ideology they profess (Fairclough, 2015; 
Risaldi, 2023. 
The presence of this research is expected to 
be used as a reference to understand the 
collective consciousness of the community in 
responding to social realities, especially in the 
cultural, social, political, and economic fields. 
From the perspective of state and non-state 
apparatus, this research is expected to be a 
reference and consideration when compiling a 
text, especially related to language choice and 
language practice. The language and linguistic 
practices used by these two parties are actually a 
space for fighting, contesting and fighting 
interests, power, and power based on certain 
ideologies. From the perspective of the audience 
as text consumers, this research is expected to be 
able to direct the audience in a more balanced 
direction, be able to sort and choose, and 
respond to a text. 
 
METHOD 
 
This research falls within the field of 
humanities. One of the approaches used in this 
field is the qualitative approach. This aligns with 
Given (2008) statement that qualitative methods 
are central to research conducted in education, 
nursing, sociology, anthropology, information 
studies, and other disciplines in the humanities, 
social sciences, and health sciences. Qualitative 
research is an investigative process that collects 
data from the context surrounding an event. This 
definition acknowledges the contextual nature of 
the investigation. 
There are several prominent characteristics 
of 
this 
qualitative 
approach. 
These 
characteristics are: first, qualitative research uses 
natural settings as its data source. Researchers 
try to observe, describe, and interpret situations 
as they are. This dissertation research uses the 
MUI Central Fatwa Text on the Shi'ah Doctrine 
of 1984 and the MUI East Java Province Fatwa 
Text on the Deviation of the Shi'ah Doctrine of 
2012 as data sources. The data collected includes 
linguistic units at the levels of vocabulary, 
grammar, and discourse derived from these 
fatwa texts. 
The object of this research material is the 
Central MUI fatwa on ""Shi'ah Understanding"" 
published in 1984 and the East Java Province 
MUI Fatwa on ""Shi'ah Sect Deviation"" in 2012 
with the number Kep-01/SKF-MUI/JTM/I/2012. 
The selection of the two fatwas from different 
sources of fatwas in terms of year is determined 
and the producer of the text is one of the 
characteristics of this dissertation. In addition,

 
 
the motive for determining the fatwa is related to 
the Shi'a understanding of the two fatwa texts 
has their own characteristics. The first has to do 
with the government's fear of the Islamic 
leadership model campaigned by the Iranian 
state through the Iranian Revolution and the 
second has to do with the turmoil and conflict 
that has taken root from the meeting of Shi'a and 
Sunni in the midst of society. This is related to 
the condition of socio-political turmoil in 
Indonesia involving Shi'a and Sunni beliefs.  
The main data in this study are vocabulary, 
grammar, and discourse contained in the MUI 
fatwa on Shi'ah understanding. The data is 
sourced from the text of the 1984 Central MUI 
fatwa on Shi'ah understanding and the text of the 
2012 East Java Province MUI Fatwa on Shi'ah 
Teachings. The discussion data is intended to 
explain the value of experience and relational 
value.  
The text of this fatwa is included in the 
written discourse section. Therefore, the method 
of collecting this research data used is the listen 
method (Sudaryanto, 2015). That is, the 
acquisition of this research data is carried out 
through the use of linguistic units in the fatwa 
text. The text of the 1984 Central MUI fatwa on 
Shi'a Understanding above is carefully examined 
to find the level of vocabulary and grammar that 
is the data for analysis. In order to run the listen 
method, supporting techniques are needed to 
select and classify data. Techniques that support 
the use of the listening method (Sudaryanto, 
2015; Mahsun, 2013) include, first, the basic 
technique of tapping in writing is used as the 
basic technique of the listening method. The use 
of written language in the fatwa text is sorted 
and selected to be the object of research related 
to the problem described.  
Second, the technique of free listening to 
engage in conversation. This technique is 
intended to select and collect vocabulary, 
grammar, synonymy, antonymy, homonymy, 
cohesion, and coherence. Third, note-taking 
techniques. The recording technique is intended 
to record and mark data that has been collected 
and selected. Furthermore, the data is adjusted to 
the focus of the study. Fourth, data triangulation 
techniques. That is, the data that has been 
recorded earlier is re-checked for validity and 
validity (Sudaryanto, 2015, Mahsun, 2013).  
The presentation of the results of this 
research analysis was delivered by informal 
methods. The informal method means an effort 
to present the results of research using ordinary 
words (Sudaryanto, 2015). The presentation of 
the results of this analysis includes data 
sequencing, data presentation, and data review.  
 
