misrepresentation by fatwa producers on Shi'a 
understanding 
is 
realized 
through 
three 
strategies, 
namely 
marginalization, 
delegitimization, and exclusivism. The data 
findings that describe the three strategies are 
explained below. 
 
Marginalization 
Marginalization is an expression of text 
producers. This expression assumes that the text 
producer is not in a neutral position. So, 
marginalization is the analysis of discourse on 
media texts which is a bad portrayal of a party or 
another group. This marginalization strategy is 
an attempt to imply by the text producer who is 
""we"" and who ""they"". Procedures carried out by 
text 
producers 
include 
euphemisms, 
dysphemisms, labeling, and stereotypes. All of 
this realizes the depiction of a person or group 
and or ideas are poorly imaged and their role is 
weakened.  
This strategy makes text consumers have a 
wrong understanding and are in a position of 
confusion. The data that shows this include the 
use 
of 
words 
""have 
basic 
differences"", ""basic differences"" and ""vigilance"". 
