Exclusivism 
Exclusion is a strategy for text producers to 
ostracize the object of writing. This exclusion 
implies that ""we"" are good and ""they"" are bad. A 
person who has a certain authority and power 
thinks that a group, idea or person is not good. 
There are several ways used by text producers to 
exclude the object of their writing, among 
others, limiting the theme of speech and the 
speaker actor and classifying based on good and 
bad. This excommunication and exclusion both 
consider a person, group, or idea to be 
something else or another person.  
Exclusivism is the third strategy of the MUI 
in presenting Shi'a understanding in its fatwa on 
Shi'a understanding. Exclusivism is an effort to 
separate the producer of text from the object of 
text. The producer thinks that the teachings he 
believes are the most correct while the teachings 
of the other party are wrong. This is the MUI's 
strategy when talking about the teachings held 
by the followers of Shi'a.  
 
 
