Shi'a understanding not in terms of religious 
freedom, but the Government is urged to 
respond to it as blasphemy. 
 
Discussion 
 
The 
motive 
for 
the 
issuance 
and 
determination of the 1984 MUI Fatwa on Shi'a is 
closely related to the socio-political conditions 
and global political developments of the early 
1980s. 
The 
export 
of 
Iranian 
revolutionary ideas targeted various countries. 
context 
prompted 
the 
New 
Order 
government to take preventive measures against 
the entry and spread of Iranian Islamic 
revolutionary ideology in Indonesia (Akmaliyah, 
2015). The initial step taken by the New Order 
government was the issuance of a Circular Letter 
through the Department of Religion regarding 
""the matter concerning the Shi'a group"" in 1983. 
Subsequently, in 1984, through the semi-
governmental body, MUI, a decree on Shi'a was 
issued. 
continuity 
implies 
MUI's 
contribution to preserving the established order 
for the New Order Government. 
The 1984 MUI Fatwa text is in a direct 
format. Although the argumentation structure is 
classical and theological, this decree has a 
political and contemporary nature. These two 
characteristics are explicitly stated through 
recommendations that specifically cite the 
vocabulary of imamah or governance. MUI 
Central chose one teaching in the Shi'a as the 
object/theme of the fatwa, not the sects within 
Shi'a. MUI only utilizes the vocabulary ""Shi'a"" 
without attributing any specific attributes. The 
utilization of the vocabulary ""Shi'a"" also 
becomes the title of the 1984 MUI Fatwa text. 
This utilization affects the level of formality of a 
discourse text (Alnizar, 2021) that merely 
intends to recommend rather than provide legal 
provisions regarding the Shi'a. 
This motive contrasts with the motive for 
the issuance of the 2012 MUI East Java Fatwa 
on the ""Deviance of Shi'a Teachings,"" which is 
related to the local socio-political conditions in 
2011-2012. The object/theme of the East Java 
MUI Fatwa is the Shi'a, particularly Imamiyah 
Itsna Asyariyah, or those using the pseudonym 
Madhhab Ahlul Bait and the like. The selection 
of Shi'a with specific attributes (Imamiyah Itsna 
Asyariyah sect) confirms that the 2012 East Java 
MUI Fatwa on the Deviance of Shi'a Teachings 
is more formal than the 1984 MUI Central Fatwa 
on Shi'a. This formality level is strategized by 
the text producers by using vocabulary such as 
""strengthen, 
establish, 
potential, 
hijacking, 
pseudonym, provocation, anarchy, conducive, 
effective, instability, legislation, freeze, prohibit, 
provocateur, 
terror, 
mental 
violence, 
comprehensive, take firm action, deviant sect, 
religious freedom, blasphemy, and NKRI 
integrity."" 
Besides vocabulary utilization, the text 
producers also use specific writing strategies. 
One such strategy is ""capitalization."" This 
capitalization is realized in the writing of 
""misleading and misguided."" This strategy 
reinforces and emphasizes what is considered 
the most important and becomes the essence of 
the 2012 East Java MUI Fatwa on the Deviance 
of Shi'a Teachings. This emphasis aligns with 
the choice of the fatwa title, ""The Deviance of 
Shi'a Teachings."" The East Java MUI Fatwa text 
follows the guidelines established by MUI 
Central. This format includes Considerations and 
Dictums resembling a legal decree. The 
formality of this format serves as an instrument 
to assert MUI's authority, attract the readers or 
consumers of the text, and mark MUI's identity 
(Alnizar, 2019; Alnizar et al, 2021). 
In the textual analysis section, the dominant 
group, MUI representing Sunni or Ahlus Sunnah 
wal Jama'ah, contests and fights for ideology and 
power over the Shi'a as a minority group. The 
chosen 
instrument 
is 
the 
utilization 
of 
vocabulary, 
grammar, 
meaning 
relations, 
cohesion, and coherence. This selection becomes 
the strategy of the text producers to assert the 
existence and position of all participants present 
in the text. This assertion is viewed from 
representation, relations, and identity (Makin, 
2017). 
From the aspect of representation, the 
subjects displayed and referred to in the text are 
Sunni, Shi'a, MUI, and the Government, both 
central and local. The Shi'a are identified, 
classified, and categorized with the label ""those

 
 
who are wrong,"" while the Sunni/Ahlus Sunnah 
wal Jama'ah are identified, classified, and 
categorized as ""we who are right."" The Shi'a 
occupy 
a 
negative 
image, 
whereas 
the 
Sunni/Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama'ah have a positive 
image. The reality of the Shi'a is represented 
through active sentences with verbal and 
material process types.  
The 
material 
of 
transitivity 
emphasizes the teachings attributed to the Shi'a 
or the facts about Shi'a used in the text 
production. Then, to strengthen these facts, the 
verbal process is depicted through the opinions 
of the participants presented in the text 
(Halliday, 2014). The verbal and material 
processes designate the Shi'a as inferior, always 
wrong, 
and 
the 
other. 
Conversely, 
the 
Sunni/Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama'ah are represented 
as superior, capable, and always right. This 
implies that MUI aims to attract and persuade 
readers to understand information about the Shi'a 
and justify and follow MUI's thoughts as the text 
producer. 
In terms of relations and identity, MUI 
strategically employs euphemism, modality, and 
modes. The softening of vocabulary represents 
the contested and fought-for ideology by the text 
producers. 
MUI 
advocates 
and 
contests 
sublimative 
ideology, 
hoping 
the 
participants 
will 
accept 
and 
believe 
the 
propositions in the fatwa. Euphemism seeks to 
soften the linguistic violence towards Shia, for 
instance, terms like ""instability,"" ""deviant,"" 
""horizontal conflict,"" and ""cutting off."" Despite 
the euphemism, MUI actually acts harshly 
towards Shia ideology through language. Terms 
such as ""reject,"" ""disparage,"" ""not believe"" are 
strategies of harsh linguistic violence employed 
by MUI (Alnizar, 2019, Alnizar et al, 2021). 
This represents a dominance ideology, where 
Sunni ideology dominates Shia ideology.  
From the sentence mode perspective, there 
are two types: interrogative and imperative. The 
choice of declarative mode represents the Shia as 
the information providers and the text consumers 
as the information receivers. The declarative 
mode functions to depict a neutral or objective 
stance and the ideology of assertion from MUI. 
This mode illustrates an oppressive ideology or 
portrays 
Shia 
as 
the 
oppressive 
group, 
suggesting an oppressive relationship between 
MUI and Shia. Examples include: ""the spread of 
Shia ideology in Indonesia, where the majority 
adheres to Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama‟ah, has a 
great potential to cause instability threatening 
the integrity of the Republic of Indonesia,"" ""the 
spread of Shia ideology targeting followers of 
Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama‟ah should be watched 
for hidden agendas,"" and ""conflicts involving 
followers of Shia Imamiyah Itsna Asyariyah 
(using pseudonyms like Madzhab Ahlul Bait) 
have frequently occurred and persisted for a long 
time."" 
Furthermore, the imperative mode, marked 
by words like ""urge,"" ""requested,"" ""asked,"" 
embodies the text producers' position in the 
fatwa as petitioners and command givers to the 
Muslim community to increase vigilance against 
the spread and entry of Shia ideology into 
Indonesia. This mode symbolizes a coordinative 
relationship or coordinative ideology.  
From the modality aspect, deontic modality 
in the fatwa text characterizes MUI as the 
deontic source with high restrictions, positioning 
the Indonesian Muslim community as the actual 
event actors. MUI positions itself as the 
authority capable of controlling Muslims and as 
the source of commands (Alnizar, 2019, Ahmad, 
2022; Ahmad et al, 2019). MUI uses deontic 
modality to control Muslims. The employment 
of doubt modality, marked by words like 
""possible,"" 
""impossible,"" 
and 
""likely,"" 
emphasizes that the spread of Shia ideology 
could happen or not. Doubt modality indicates 
MUI‟s uncertainty about the events. It suggests 
that MUI has not exercised its power or done 
anything yet, indicating the text producer's lack 
of confidence in the truth of the propositions 
conveyed. The use of certainty modality implies 
MUI's attitude and belief. The necessity 
modality, marked by words like ""required,"" 
presupposes that the information presented by 
MUI is based on known facts. In the 
recommendation dictum, MUI emphasizes its 
stance for the audience to follow up on its intent, 
influenced by the willingness of the Central or 
Local Government, the Muslim community, and 
the Central MUI. 
Generally, the Central MUI and MUI of 
East Java aim to reinforce dominant ideology, 
marginalization ideology, Islamism ideology, 
exclusivism ideology, and apophatism ideology 
through the fatwa texts related to Shia. MUI 
represents itself as the Indonesian Muslim 
community adhering to Ahlus Sunnah wal 
Jama‟ah. This strategy is an effort by MUI to

  
participate in contesting and fighting for the 
arena of discourse and religious authority in 
Indonesia. This effort is accompanied by 
labeling Shia ideology as ""having differences,"" 
""increasing vigilance,"" ""potential to cause unrest 
and 
horizontal 
conflict,"" 
""ushuliyah,"" 
""furu'iyah,"" 
""incompatible,"" 
""not 
acknowledging,"" 
""disparaging,"" 
""denying,"" 
""cannot 
be 
united,"" 
""causing 
instability,"" 
""threatening the integrity of the Republic of 
Indonesia,"" and ""religious blasphemy."" This is 
demonstrated and proven by labeling Shia as 
""deviant and misleading,"" absolutely placing 
Shia in an out-grouping position (Makin, 2017). 
Another synthesized aspect from the textual 
study 
is 
MUI 
also 
adheres 
to 
a 
""phallocentric"" ideology. This is pursued by 
MUI referring to itself as the ""big tent"" of 
Muslims and khadimul ummah (Hakim, 2020;  
Alnizar, 2021). These two concepts symbolize 
power, with MUI considering itself as the holder 
of religious authority in Indonesia. This naming 
is an effort by MUI to elevate its authority and 
control the discourse. 
The situational context of social-political 
conditions and global political developments in 
the early 1980s motivated the issuance of the 
Central MUI fatwa on Shia ideology in 1984. 
The recommendation in the fatwa, highlighting 
""imamah"" or ""leadership,"" cannot be separated 
from 
the 
political 
situation 
post-Iranian 
Revolution and the establishment of the Islamic 
Republic of Iran. This event was suspected of 
exporting revolutionary ideas (Makin, 2017). 
1979 marked the year of the Iranian Revolution, 
which overthrew and replaced the secular 
government with an Islamic government. The 
reverberation of the Iranian Revolution reached 
beyond Iran, even to Indonesia. 
Global political conditions in the late 1970s 
and early 1980s influenced the stance of the 
New Order government led by President 
Soeharto at that time (Akmaliyah, 2019, Hakim, 
2021). 
The 
seeds 
of 
Islamist 
ideology 
developing in Indonesia were detected by the 
Old Order government, leading to the issuance 
of Law No. 1/PNPS/1965 on Prevention of 
Abuse and/or Blasphemy of Religion. The 
success 
of 
the 
""Iranian 
Revolution"" 
in 
overthrowing the government in Iran in 1979 
also resonated in Indonesia. The New Order 
government realized that the entry of Shia 
ideology into Indonesia was gradual. With the 
entry of Shia ideology, the New Order 
government felt threatened. The New Order 
government took several steps, including the 
obligation of a single Pancasila ideology, the 
MPR Decree No. II/MPR/1983 on the Broad 
Guidelines of State Policy (GBHN) containing 
the obligation to make Pancasila the sole 
ideology, the Ministry of Religion Circular No. 
D/BA.01/4865/1983, dated December 5, 1983, 
on ""The Shia Sect."" The culmination was in 
1984, when the government, through the Central 
MUI, issued a fatwa on Shia ideology.  
fatwa 
explicitly 
anticipated 
and 
warned against imamah. It clearly stated, 
""considering 
the 
fundamental 
differences 
between Shia and Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama‟ah as 
mentioned above, especially regarding the 
difference 
on 
'Imamah' 
(leadership),"" 
the 
Indonesian Ulema Council through its 1984 
fatwa on Shia ideology urged Indonesian 
Muslims adhering to Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama‟ah 
to increase vigilance against the potential entry 
of Shia-based ideology."" Therefore, MUI's 
existence during the New Order era was as an 
extension 
of 
the 
Soeharto 
government 
(Akmaliyah, 2015). 
If 
the 
global 
socio-political 
context 
influenced the issuance of the Central MUI 
fatwa on Shia in 1984, the local socio-political 
context and political developments (Alnizar, 
2019) particularly in East Java provinces 
inhabited by Shia followers, became the 
background, reason, and urgency for the East 
Java MUI fatwa on the Deviation of Shia 
Teachings in 2012. The East Java MUI deemed 
it necessary to have guidelines to safeguard the 
faith of the community from deviations from 
Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama‟ah. The East Java MUI 
was requested, urged, and asked by several 
institutions such as local MUI branches in East 
Java, BASSRA, PCNU Sampang Regency, and 
the Forum of Kyai and Ulema.  
These institutions pushed East Java MUI to 
take a stance on the presence of Ustad Tajul 
Muluk and his followers who adhered to Shia 
ideology and the spread of Shia ideology in East 
Java Province (Ahmad, 2019). The East Java 
MUI eventually declared and affirmed that Shia 
ideology is ""deviant and misleading."" Ideally, 
the community views this fatwa as aiming to 
protect the majority ideology and position the 
minority ideology equally. This protection and 
positioning are internalized in both fatwas.

 
 
CONCLUSIONS 
 
The Central MUI fatwa text on ""Shia 
Ideology"" in 1984 and the East Java MUI fatwa 
text on the ""Deviation of Shia Teachings"" in 
2012 are forms of discourse. This implies that 
fatwa texts serve as social semiotics. These 
fatwa texts are concrete manifestations of 
language use. Language use in society becomes 
a social practice. Vocabulary and grammar are 
tools utilized and fought for by text producers. 
These two elements represent experiential value 
and relational value. Both values embody the 
positioning, existence, and affirmation towards 
Shia and Sunni (Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama‟ah) 
ideologies. 
Based on vocabulary and grammar aspects, 
Shia ideology is asserted and judged as wrong, 
whereas Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama‟ah ideology is 
asserted and judged as right. This judgment is 
articulated in the experiential and relational 
values contained in the choice and use of 
vocabulary and grammar in the fatwa texts on 
Shia ideology. This selection and utilization 
reflect the ""right and wrong"" parameters labeled 
to both Ahlus Sunnah wal Jama‟ah and Shia 
ideologies.","This writing aims to synthesize the misrepresentation strategy presented by the MUI in its fatwa on Shia. This writing is a descriptive qualitative type with a critical paradigm approach. The data sources for this writing are the Central Indonesian Ulema Council's 1984 Fatwa on Shia Beliefs and the 2012 East Java Provincial Indonesian Ulema Council's Fatwa on the Deviance of Shia Teachings. The research data consists of the vocabulary and grammar utilized and selected by the MUI in the fatwa on Shia. This issue is examined through Norman Fairclough's critical discourse analysis, including the experiential value and relational value of vocabulary and grammar. The results of this research show that the MUI, in its fatwa on Shia, displays and orchestrates with an excommunication approach. The fatwa succeeds in expressing the practice of domination by the fatwa producers over the followers of Shia beliefs. The fatwa successfully becomes a discourse that holds power. This is represented through linguistic units referenced to Shia beliefs. The MUI chooses and supports Sunni beliefs while marginalizing Shia beliefs. The representation of the linguistic units utilized by the MUI presents Shia beliefs as incorrect while portraying Sunni beliefs as correct. This shows the presence of misrepresentation or incorrect depiction by the text producers. This strategy is called a misrepresentation strategy. The model of misrepresentation employed by the MUI includes marginalization, delegitimization, and exclusivity.MISREPRESENTATION OF THE INDONESIAN ULEMA COUNCILIN FATWAS ON SHI'A: NORMAN FAIRCLOUGH MODEL OF CRITICAL DISCOURSE ANALYSIS"
"THE USE OF REFERENCE AS MARKERS OF PROPOSITIONAL 
RELATIONS IN JUNIOR HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS’ ESSAYS 
Abdul Wahid, Andi Sukri Syamsuri, Andi Hasrianti, Alfi Syahrin 
1 Fakultas Keguruan dan Ilmu Pendidikan, Universitas Muhammadiyah Makassar 
2,3 Universitas Islam Negeri Alauddin Makassar 
4 Fakultas Keguruan dan Ilmu Pendidikan, Universitas Almuslim 
1 Jl. Sultan Alauddin No.259, Kota Makassar, Sulawesi Selatan 
2,3 Jl. Sultan Alauddin No. 36, Samata, Kabupaten Gowa 
4 Jl. Almuslim, Matangglumpangdua, Bireuen, Aceh 
 
Article History:  
Submitted: 20 April 2024; Revised: 23 July 2024, Accepted: 24 July 2024 
 
 
RETORIKA: Jurnal Bahasa, Sastra dan Pengajarannya under 
 Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License. 
 
 
Abstract: The purpose of this study was to evaluate the use of reference as markers of 
propositional relations in essays written by junior high school students. This study employed a 
qualitative method in data collection and data analysis. The population and research samples were 
94 eighth-grade students from SMP Negeri 1 in Balikpapan, Indonesia, ranging in age from 13 to 
14. Data collection in this research was carried out using the listening method after the essay as a 
source of research data obtained from the research sample.The data analysis in this study consisted 
of three stages that were completed interactively: data reduction, data display, and conclusion 
drawing. This study suggest that participants utilized three distinct kinds of reference to denote 
propositional relations in their essays: third-person pronoun, non-person pronoun, and 
demonstrative pronoun. The third person pronoun was found to be widely used but did not vary 
significantly among participants. Meanwhile, participants’ usage of non-person pronouns resulted 
in numerous interpretations, and it was discovered that derived demonstrative pronouns were 
overused. These findings demonstrate the participants’ strengths and shortcomings in using 
reference to connect one proposition to another. 
 
Keywords: markers of relations, reference, propositions, essays, junior high school students 
 
Writing is widely recognized as an 
important language skill (Bobkina & Dominguez, 
2014; Dumlao & Wilang, 2019; Favart et al., 
2016; Hassan et al., 2016; Pham, 2021; 
Pospelova, 2021; Smirnova, 2019; Wahid et al., 
2020), but it is complex to be mastered by every 
language user for both native and non-native 
speakers 
(Adeyemi, 
2017; 
Ahmad, 
2019; 
Alhojailan, 2021; Styati & Rodliyah, 2021). 
Regardless of their writing abilities, all writers 
understand the complicated process of writing 
(Crossley & McNamara, 2010; Kohlani, 2010; 
Wijana, 2006).  
In written communication, writers must be 
able to organize and present ideas effectively. In 
other words, writers must organize their ideas 
coherently and rationally in order to stay on 
subject. Coherently composing ideas entails 
arranging them in a consistent manner, without 
suffering 
jumps 
in 
thought, 
and 
logical 
arrangement entails putting them in a way that is 
acceptable to reason (Gunawan et al., 2020; Rani

  
et al., 2013). The organization of such concepts 
is critical for writers because context does not 
always exist without a clear explanation, which 
allows ideas or propositions to be conveyed 
completely. Writers in written communication 
are in a context-reduced situation (Ivanič, 2004). 
That is, the presence of context is not strong 
enough to accompany the ideas delivered 
through written communication. Thus, when 
communicating ideas, writers must truly present 
a comprehensive, clear, and logical explanation 
so that they can be easily understood by the 
readers (Safnil, 2010).  
The use of references contributes to the 
quality of writing because it connects the 
previous proposition with the next proposition 
(Smirnova, 2019). Anaphora references are often 
used in various text genres, making them an 
important topic for learning writing in schools 
(Crompton, 2017). However, students in junior 
high school are language learners who are just 
learning to express propositions in writing. Their 
thinking and written language skills are still in a 
transitional stage (Wahid et al., 2020; Wahid & 
Marni, 2018). Therefore, there is a possibility 
that propositional relations that are built through 
markers of reference relations in students' essays 
in junior high school will show logical relations 
on the one hand and show forms that seem 
distorted on the other. As stated by Smirnova, 
(2019) that L writers have difficulty in using 
effective anaphoric references because anaphora 
is a fairly complex linguistic feature whose 
accurate use requires maturity of knowledge and 
high language proficiency. The use of references 
in students' essays will tend to lead to multiple 
and redundant interpretations, resulting in 
incoherence of propositions in their essays. Even 
so, the form of deviation that appears in the 
essays of students in junior high school cannot 
be used as a benchmark that they are not able to 
write well. On the contrary, it is possible that 
they have used their ability to build propositional 
relations by choosing certain forms of reference 
relation markers so that the propositions 
presented in their essays appear to be related to 
each other, even though the realization of the 
forms presented is not acceptable. For this 
reason, research findings can be assumed to have 
an important position that is useful for 
practitioners, researchers, teachers, and students 
at the junior high school level to show the 
difficulties and challenges of students in 
utilizing references in their writings. 
Reference as a linguistic device that plays 
an important role in forming a coherent text has 
been explored by a number of scholars. This is 
especially widely explored using the theoretical 
framework of Halliday & Hasan's (1976) 
cohesion device (eg Coyle et al. 2020; Bowen & 
Thomas 2020; Struthers et al., 2013; Tsareva, 
2010; Crossley & McNamara, 2010; Ghufron, 
2012; Bahaziq, 2016; Favart et al., 2016; 
Briesmaster & Etchegaray, 2017; Adeyemi, 
2017).  Some of these scholars studied the use of 
cohesion devices in various genres of student 
writing, but did not discuss specifically on the 
use of references as a means of linking one 
proposition to another in junior high school 
students' writing. Thus, in recent years, the 
number of studies related to references has 
begun to be highlighted by several institutions. 
Plakans & Gebril (2017), for example, studying 
anaphors and logical operators as a measure of 
cohesion in a TOEFL iBT writing task report 
that the effect size for anaphor references is 
smaller for logical operators. Another interesting 
study conducted by Smirnova (2019) who 
studied referential coherence in academic 
writings of Russian students reported that 
students use anaphoric references less frequently 
than professional writers because students face 
some 
difficulties 
when 
using 
anaphoric 
references in their writing. Al Sharoufi (2014) 
also analyzed the use of reference anaphora, 
cataphora, and transition markers in L students' 
academic essays claiming that the use of 
referential elements causes some difficulties for 
students. However, this researcher did not 
determine the specific problems in the use of the 
analyzed 
anaphora. 
Meanwhile, 
Leńko-
Szimańska, (2004), who studied specifically the 
forms of demonstrative abuse in Polish student 
essays concluded that most students overuse 
demonstratives. Another finding reported that 
Polish students tend to abuse the use of the 
demonstrative form.  
There have been many previous studies 
investigating the use of cohesive devices in 
various genres of student writing and reporting 
on the relationship between cohesion features 
and student essay quality. However, research 
related to references in students' essays in junior 
high schools seems to be very limited. Thus, the 
characteristics of using references as a means to

 
 
link one proposition to another in students' 
essays at the junior high school level have not 
been explored. Investigating the form of use of 
reference markers 
can facilitate a better 
understanding of how essay coherence is 
achieved by students at the junior secondary 
level. In addition, the realization of students' 
written language which tends to be influenced by 
various factors such as cognitive development, 
language development, and learning to write can 
show a form of students' thinking and written 
language maturity in utilizing references in 
forming a cohesive essay. For this reason, this 
study tries to analyze the relation of propositions 
in student essays which are built through the use 
of reference markers. These findings are then 
discussed and related to language development, 
psychological 
development, 
and 
language 
learning. This kind of discussion has not been 
studied extensively by previous researchers. 
Thus, the focus of this research is a topic of 
study that can fill and enrich the repertoire of 
written discourse studies in the context of 
student writing in junior high school. 
 
METHOD 
 
This study used a qualitative approach to 
data collection and data analysis. Qualitative 
research is a type of social science research that 
relies on non-numeric data, often in textual form 
(Saunders et al., 2009), and aims to provide in-
depth descriptions in real contexts and focus on 
ordinary, naturally occurring events (Miles et al., 
2014). This study employed a qualitative 
approach because it has a natural background or 
context. The phenomena in this study were 
investigated through the collection of empirical 
data and texts, which helped to provide detailed 
and flexible descriptions for use as data sources 
Denzin & Lincoln, 2005). From a linguistic 
perspective, this study falls within the category 
of discourse analysis, which focuses on the 
internal features of discourse. The internal 
feature that was examined was the use of 
reference terms to denote relationships between 
propositions in student writings. Due to its 
discourse analysis viewpoint, this study drew on 
the analytical model of the reference tool 
presented by Halliday & Hasan (1976).  
The study enrolled 94 eighth-grade students 
from SMP Negeri 1 Balikpapan, who were 
separated into VIII.1, VIII.2, and VIII.3. The 
study’s participants ranged in age from 13 to 14 
years old. These language learners are in the late 
stages 
of 
adolescence, 
transitioning 
from 
childhood to late adolescence. In terms of 
thinking abilities, participants generally possess 
the capacity to reason logically, abstractly, and 
complexly (Schunk, 2012), which enables them 
to produce logical and complex written language 
through the incorporation of reference words as 
markers of propositional relations in their essays. 
Additionally, their development of written 
language is influenced by a variety of elements, 
including 
situational/environmental 
circumstances 
and 
the 
learning 
process. 
Therefore, the realization of language and 
propositions 
are 
built 
through 
the 
enrichment of these relations have distinctive 
characteristics. 
Data collection in this study was carried out 
using the “close reading” method, following the 
collection of student essays. These essays are a 
separate classroom assignment because SMP 
Negeri 
Balikpapan 
does 
not 
have 
documentation of the essays of eighth grade 
students. 
The 
assignment 
technique 
was 
accomplished by providing target participants 
with writing instructions. The participants were 
given the flexibility to express their thoughts in 
the form of an essay during the writing process 
(observation or non-observation). Thus, (a) 
participants will have greater freedom to 
communicate their ideas, (b) the language and 
propositions suggested by participants will be 
realized according to their interests, and (c) 
participants will not perceive an intervention, 
allowing them to explore more and write down 
as many ideas as possible. 
The research tool includes instructions to 
writing essay. The instrument was developed in 
accordance with the three-stage writing process 
model, which consists of planning, translation, 
and review. The research instrument contains all 
three stages implicitly. Prior to usage, the 
instrument was evaluated to establish its 
practicality level. Another group of eighth 
graders was subjected to the instrument trial 
twice. After several rounds of testing and 
revising, the instrument was utilized to collect 
data for this study (student essay). 
Data collection started from August to 
September 2019. It was carried out in Bahasa

  
Indonesian classes within the time frame agreed 
upon with the school, so it did not interfere with 
the students’ regular school schedule. Three 
Indonesian teachers were involved in the data 
collection proces. The teachers  were in charge 
of reading the instructions and directing students 
throughout the essay writing process. This was 
done to ensure the participants’ compliance and 
earnestness while composing the essay. The 
provision of writing instructions was carried out 
in accordance with the stages in writing, namely 
planning, translation, and review.  
Data analysis in this study was conducted 
using Miles et al. (2014). This model depicts 
four activity flows, three of which were used in 
this research’s data analysis, namely data 
reduction, data display, and conclusion drawing. 
The data reduction stage involved an intense 
reading of the data, followed by sorting and 
categorization of data according to the research 
objective. At this point, each variable under 
investigation was coded. The second stage was 
data visualization, which is the compilation of a 
collection of data that enables the drawing of 
conclusions and taking action. The statistics 
were presented technically in the form of 
narratives, tables, and charts. The presentation 
of the data enables us to determine whether the 
data acquired were adequate and sufficient or if 
extra analysis was required. At the third stage, 
conclusion drawing, the findings were analyzed 
and 
connected 
to 
pre-existing 
theories. 
Conclusions were drawn continually until 
precise findings regarding the use of reference 
as markers of propositional relations in student 
essay were acquired. 
 
 
RESULTS AND DISCUSSION 
 
Research Results 
According to data analysis of 94 essays 
written by eighth-grade students at SMP Negeri 
1, three distinct types of reference were 
identified as propositional relation markers. The 
three types of reference are third-person 
pronoun, 
non-person 
pronoun, 
and 
demonstrative pronoun. The three categories of 
reference are presented in Table 1. 
 
