Third Person Pronoun 
Third-person pronouns in both singular 
(polite him/her) and plural forms (them) were 
utilized as identifiers of relationships between 
propositions in the participants’ essays. The two 
forms of the third-person pronoun seen in the 
participants’ essays are anaphoric, which is 
referred to words put in a propositional range 
and placed before the third-person pronoun in 
the following range of propositions. The 
following excerpt presents the use of third-
person pronoun in student essay. 
 
 (01). (a) Mrs. Sumarni works at SMP 
Negeri 1 Balikpapan as a librarian. (b) 
Beliau/She is an honest and firm person. (c) 
Beliau/She often keeps the library clean 
(MA/8.3/P.3/PRR) 
 
In data (01), the third person singular 
pronoun ""She"" is mentioned twice. The first 
""she"" appears in proposition (b), while the 
second ""she"" appears in proposition (c). The use 
of beliau (polite she/he) “she is an honest 
person (...) and in “she often keeps the library 
clean” (...) both relate to the same individual.

 
 
Mrs. Sumarni is that individual, as she is the 
only one named in the prior proposition. This 
reference system is anaphoric. The relationship 
between she and Sumarni in data (01) shows 
the relationship between propositions within 
sentences. She in propositions (b) and (c) serves 
as a signifier of their connection to propositions 
(a), allowing the essay to form a unified whole 
around a single topic. 
  
(02). (a) The cooperative was founded in 
1989 and currently employs two people, 
namely Om Oki and Om Herman. (b) They 
provide excellent service to customers. 
(AZ/8.1/P.1/PRR) 
 
In data (02), the plural third-person 
