Non-Personal Pronoun 
Non-person pronouns are those that refer 
to objects other than individuals. The object 
being referred can be animated or inert. The 
non-person pronoun was utilized in this study to 
denote the relationship between propositions. 
The pronoun relates to the proposition’s 
inanimate object, which was introduced initially. 
The object to which reference is being made is 
a 
location 
name. 
The 
following 
data 
demonstrates how pronoun “its” is used to 
denote the relationship between propositions.   
 
(03). (a) I love this classroom. (b) not dirty, 
comfortable, and cold. (c) Its decorations 
are also nice and pleasing to the eye 
(STA/8.1/P.5/PRR) 
 
The pronoun “its” appears in data (03). In 
the proposition, the pronoun appears in the 
phrase ""its decorations"" (c). The pronoun ""its"" 
is anaphorically used to refer to an inanimate 
noun that is surrounded in or attached to ""its 
decorations"" (the name of a place). The 
location referred to in the preceding proposition 
is ""this classroom."" In light of the preceding 
propositions, the expression ""this classroom"" 
refers to class 8.1 in this instance. In data (03), 
the pronoun ""its"" is used in conjunction with 
""its decorations"" to provide context for the 
previous proposition’s topic. Additionally, it 
serves as a relation marker, indicating that 
propositions (a) and (c) are related. The third 
pronoun ""its"" connects proposition (c) to 
proposition (a), forming a coherent writing unit. 
Without the pronoun ""its"" in proposition (c) and 
""this 
classroom"" 
in 
statement 
(a), 
the 
propositional link is shaky and its meaning is 
