Discussion 
 
According to the findings of this study, 
three distinct categories of reference were 
identified as markers of propositional relations: 
third person pronouns, non-person pronouns, 
and demonstrative pronouns. The third-person 
pronouns found in research participants’ essays 
is the single version of the person pronoun 
""Beliau"" (polite he/she) and the plural ""they."" 
The non-person pronoun that was discovered in 
this study takes the form of the pronoun ""its."" 
Meanwhile, demonstrative pronouns included 
in the students’ essays are classified into three 
types: basic demonstrative pronouns (this/these 
and that/those), derived demonstrative pronouns 
(the), and compound demonstrative pronouns 
(here, around the area, there). In contrast to this 
study’s findings, (Halliday & Hasan, 1976, 
1985) argue that there are three categories of 
references: 
personal, 
demonstrative, 
and 
comparative. The results of this study also 
differ from research results such as Gutierrez-
Clellen & Heinrichs-Ramos (1993), Sánchez et 
al. (2013),  Tsareva (2010),  Ghufron, (2012), 
Favart et al. (2016), Briesmaster & Etchegaray 
(2017), Adeyemi, (2017), and Mora et al. 
(2021).  
Demonstrative pronoun references are 
more prevalent in junior high school students’ 
essays 
than 
non-person 
and 
third-person 
reference. It is inextricably linked to the type of 
essay submitted by the participants. The 
majority of essays written by the participants 
are descriptive in nature. A descriptive essay 
discusses how something is in its current state 
or how something functions in its current state 
(Wiratno, 
2018). 
Additionally, 
Wiratno 
explains that a descriptive essay is concerned 
with the unique features of the object being 
described, such as its shape, size, color, flavor, 
and other physical properties . Objects, people, 
locations, and atmosphere are frequently 
detailed 
in 
descriptive 
text 
paragraphs 
(Indiyastini, 2009). The participants in this 
study primarily described items, places, and 
atmospheres. 
As 
a 
result, 
pronouns were more frequently used by the 
participants to indicate relationships between 
propositions than non-person or third-person 
pronouns. 
As previously stated, this study’s findings 
reveal that two distinct types of third person 
pronouns were used as propositional relation 
markers in the participants’ writings. The plural 
third person pronoun ""they"" and the single form 
of third person pronoun ""Beliau"" (polite she/he) 
are the two forms. Meanwhile, essays written 
by the participants did not make use of 
alternative third-person pronouns such as ""she 
or he"" as markers of propositional relations. 
The participants employed the third person 
pronoun ""they"" to refer to the noun or to more 
than one person being spoken about. Similarly, 
the singular form of the third person pronoun 
""Beliau"" was used to refer to a single individual 
being talked, in accordance with the third 
person pronoun’s role, which is to refer to the 
individual being discussed in a text (Alwi et al., 
2003; Effendi et al., 2015).  
The use of third person pronouns (they and 
Beliau) in the participants’ essays can be 
deemed to have met the requirements for 
successful 
reference 
use 
as 
markers 
of 
propositional relationships. Fox (1987) asserts 
that references can be made successfully (e.g., 
through the use of pronouns) if they are focused, 
conscious, textually derived, or highly topical, 
and can be operationally defined within the 
context of discourse structures. Successful 
references in an essay should meet the 
following criteria: (a) the reader can clearly 
identify the antecedent, (b) the message is 
delivered to the reader, (c) the reader can 
quickly grasp the author’s goal, and (d) there is 
a clear connection between the word referred to 
and the pronoun used. The participants’ usage 
of third person pronouns (they and Beliau) has 
an obvious reference (antecedent). This is seen 
in data (01) and data (02). 
The success of the participants in using the 
third person pronoun references is possible 
because of the age of the participants. As stated 
by Saville-Troike (2006), age is one of the 
factors that influence the success of language 
learners. The increasing age of language

 
 
learners contributes to the improvement of 
students’ analytical skills and language learning 
competencies. By the age of eight, students are 
generally able to provide clear and cohesive 
narratives 
(Mora 
et 
al., 
2021), 
 
but 
sophistication in the use of cohesive devices 
continues to develop into adolescence (Bahaziq, 
2016; Neisi & Gorjian, 2017; Wilks, 2005). The 
development of reference use in adolescence 
keeps increasing which is marked by a 
reduction in ambiguity in its use (Guthire, 2008; 
Kwan & Yunus, 2014).  
Personal pronouns are generally acquired 
by children at the age of 2 years. This is 
consistent with Nancy's (1983) research on the 
stages of language development in children, 
which indicates that by the age of two years, 
many 
youngsters 
have 
learned 
personal 
pronouns. Children at that age, she asserts, are 
already capable of using personal pronouns 
such as me, you, and him, while more forms of 
personal pronouns used by children are 
unknown at this time. Personal pronouns are 
gradually acquired by adolescents and evolve in 
tandem with their age and understanding. This 
was revealed in a developmental study of 
children, who demonstrated that by the age of 
ten, children can appropriately arrange personal 
pronouns in their narrative writing using 
anaphora patterns (Akinci & Decool-Mercier, 
2010). 
The success of the participants in using 
personal pronouns as markers of propositional 
relations is not only influenced by maturity of 
thinking (cognitive), but also influenced by 
cultural background. In other words, the 
participants’ 
accuracy 
when 
sorting 
and 
selecting personal pronouns is highly dependent 
on their language and cultural background. 
Each language has its own set of norms and 
cultural context that are distinct from those of 
other languages (Setiawan, 2015). These 
distinctions have ramifications for any speaker 
or writer who use personal pronouns in oral or 
written 
communication. 
In 
English, 
speakers/writers simply use the term “you” to 
refer to a second person singular regardless of 
who is being addressed, whether it is a child, 
adolescent, or parent. In contrast to English, to 
use the second person singular in Indonesian, 
the speaker/writer must first determine who is 
being addressed. This information is critical 
because it impacts the effectiveness of oral and 
written communication. For instance, a student 
who addresses a teacher with the term “you“ is 
most emphatically not appropriate, as the word 
is typically used by someone who has a close 
relationship with the other person or by an older 
person to a younger person. 
The existence of a link between cultural 
background and the system of personal 
pronouns in Indonesian ultimately leads every 
speaker/writer to select personal pronoun 
references (first, second, and third) in their 
mental dictionary. This also holds true for the 
participants, as the majority are language users 
who grew up speaking Indonesian as their 
mother tongue (native language). Before 
utilizing personal pronouns as markers of 
propositional relations, participants must first 
pick elements of personal pronouns in their 
mental dictionaries that are regarded to be 
consistent with cultural norms. As indicated in 
data (02), the third person pronoun ""Beliau"" 
(polite she/he) is intended to reference an older 
individual or instructor at the student’s school. 
Despite the fact that the terms ""he and she"" 
were already in the participant’s mental 
dictionary, the participant chose not to use them 
since 
they 
contradicted 
the 
participant’s 
purpose of respecting the person being 
discussed. 
This 
demonstrates 
the 
participant is already aware of the standard, as 
seen by his ability to employ the third person 
as 
a 
marker 
of 
propositional 
relationships appropriately, thoughtfully, and 
politely. This research corroborates Nippold 
(2006) assertion that teenagers are generally 
adept at changing their oral/written modes of 
communication to the needs of the audience. 
Additionally, they appreciate the value of 
speaking more professionally and properly 
while conversing with teachers, older relatives, 
or children. 
Following that, the pronoun ""its"" was 
discovered as a marker of the relation that 
connects one proposition to the next in the 
participants’ essays. The participants’ usage of 
the pronoun ""its"" relates to a non-human term 
(or thing). As a result, the pronoun ""its"" was not 
classified as a variation of the third person 
pronoun in this situation, as the pronoun ""its"" 
does not relate to a human (person). According 
to  (Rani et al., 2013) and Indiyastini (2009), 
some pronouns serve as cohesion devices and 
refer to humans, while others relate to non-

  
humans. Non-person pronouns are pronouns 
that do not refer to humans. 
In addition, the participants used the 
pronoun ""its"" to refer to non-human objects. 
The items to which this pronoun refers are the 
names of a place (such as the library, the 
laboratory, the class, and the prayer room). The 
reference to these items came up as a result of 
the participants identifying the names of places 
in their school environment as potential sources 
of 
information 
for 
essay 
writing. 
The 
participants had a significant interest in the 
school environment, particularly in visible 
objects. This is consistent with the cognitive 
traits of the individuals, who fall into the 
category of early adolescence in this context. 
According to Kellogg (2008), early adolescents 
are often interested in real-world experiences 
and 
realistic 
learning 
techniques. 
Early 
adolescents seek opportunities to investigate 
their world (Manning, 2002; Schunk, 2012), 
although this exploration is still limited to the 
observation time currently in place. 
In this study, the junior high school 
students wrote essays about actual objects 
found in their classroom surroundings. In other 
words, the participants built assertions based on 
tangible topics taught in their schools. This is 
because words that depict physical (visual) 
images are more accessible to children and 
early adolescents than ones that allude to 
abstract notions. Due to the predominance of 
tangible terms from the school environment, the 
assertions in students’ writings took the form of 
descriptive statements and propositions about 
specific objects. The specifics of the object 
components ultimately prompted participants to 
employ the reference pronoun ""its"" as a marker 
of propositional relations in their essays. 
The pronoun ""its"" is an anaphoric marker 
of propositional relation in the participants’ 
essays. That is, the antecedent (or the object to 
which it refers) appears in the preceding 
proposition or is immediately to the left of the 
sentence containing ""its."" The anaphoric design 
was chosen by the participants for its 
accessibility. Anaphoric references are simple 
to write because the items being referred to 
have already been introduced (written down) in 
the writer’s working memory and are therefore 
more easily associated with pronouns (the 
pronoun ""its""). Apart from simplifying the 
writing process for writers, the usage of 
anaphoric patterns can also aid readers in 
comprehending the text. The use of anaphoric 
references can assist readers in locating the 
constituents intended by the text’s author, hence 
shortening the reading process. 
The findings of this study also reveal that 
the pronoun ""its"" was employed in two ways in 
the participants’ writings. To begin, some 
participants employed the non-person pronoun 
""its"" as a marker of the relationship between 
propositions in order to create a coherent 
composition, whereas others used ""its"" in an 
ambiguous manner. This can be seen in data (03) 
and data (04). The pronoun ""its"" used in data (4) 
lends itself to many interpretations. The use of 
the pronoun ""its"" is ambiguous in this instance 
because the author introduced two nouns 
(things) before the pronoun ""its,"" making the 
relation unclear. In contrast to the findings of 
this study, Ambridge & Lieven (2011) and 
Matthews et al. (2009) have noted that children 
have trouble with ambiguous pronouns and 
frequently avoid them until around the age of 
six years. The participants in this study were 
pre-adolescents between the ages of 13 and 14. 
As a result, it appears as though some of them 
are still having difficulty with pronouns, 
particularly the pronoun ""its."" 
Along with third pronouns and non-person 
pronouns, the essays of the participants also 
contained 
pronouns. 
The 
demonstrative pronouns discovered fall into 
three categories: basic demonstrative pronouns 
(this/these 
and 
that/those), 
demonstrative pronouns (the), and combination 
demonstrative pronouns (here, around the area, 
there). All of these demonstrative pronouns are 
used in respective writings as identifiers for 
propositional relations. However, each of these 
demonstrative pronouns has a slightly different 
interpretation and function as a marker of 
propositional relations in the participants’ 
essays: 
and 
pronouns are used to refer to an object and are 
frequently not used to clarify the object’s 
position, whereas combined demonstrative 
pronouns are used to determine the place’s 
position. The three demonstrative pronouns 
exhibit varying degrees of usage in the 
participants’ essays. The usage of derived 
demonstrative pronouns is far more prevalent 
than the use of the other two demonstrative

 
 
pronouns (basic or combined demonstrative 
reference). 
The 
employed 
the 
demonstrative pronoun ""the"" to refer to the 
antecedent (or component of a proposition) in a 
variety of previously mentioned propositions. 
This is consistent with Suyitno's (2012)  
interpretation of the term ""the"" as ""already 
mentioned."" Additionally, Suyitno explains that 
the word ""the"" serves as a descriptor for a word, 
phrase, or possibly an additional grammatical 
unit. The derived demonstrative pronoun ""the"" 
is almost universally used as a marker of 
propositional relations in the writings of the 
participants. However, its application is little 
understood. 
Certain 
participant 
writings 
repeatedly employ the term ""the"" in a variety of 
assertions, resulting in redundant references. 
The following excerpt demonstrates this. 
The participant who wrote the above 
excerpt appears to use the derived pronoun 
""the"" to refer to the same referent in a 
propositional range, namely four cupboards. As 
a result, superfluous repeating of references 
occurs. The demonstrative pronoun ""the"" can 
actually be omitted from the excerpt above to 
make it more effective. If this is done correctly, 
the proposition of the phrase ""There are four 
cupboards in Musalah Tursina: one for Al-
Quran storage, two for mukenah storage, and 
one for musholla equipment storage."" This type 
of immersion will aid in the comprehension of 
the sentence. 
Another demonstrative pronoun that the 
participants used to denote propositional links 
is the basic demonstrative pronoun ""this/these”. 
Alwi et al. (2003) classify the pronoun 
""this/these"" as a broad indicating pronoun. The 
demonstrative pronoun ""this/these"" is used by 
the participants to refer to the elements of the 
proposition indicated previously, when the 
antecedent is in front of or to the left of the 
sentence containing ""this/these."" Suyitno (2012,) 
notes, however, that the pointer ""this/these"" can 
also 
point 
backwards 
or 
cataphorically. 
Unfortunately, the participants’ essays do not 
contain the cataphoric demonstrative pronoun 
""this/these"" because the students might have 
trouble 
accessing 
cataphoric 
references. 
Cataphoric references are typically more 
challenging to design than anaphoric references, 
as the author must consider the reader’s ability 
to identify the antecedent (Brasoveanu, 2006).  
On the other side, the study’s participants are 
less sensitive, less confident, and less observant 
when it comes to writing cataphoric references 
(Petchprasert, 2013).  
The findings of this study suggest that the 
basic demonstrative pronoun ""this/these"" does 
not always add to the cohesion of the 
participants’ essays. For instance, in data (5), 
the participant uses the basic demonstrative 
pronoun ""these"" to refer to the propositional 
element of the phrase that was introduced 
initially. However, its use does not establish a 
logical connection between the sentence’s 
propositions. The propositional relation is 
irrational since the order in which the 
propositions are presented is not systematic. In 
other words, the illogicality occurs not as a 
result of the participant’s incorrect use of the 
basic demonstrative pronoun ""these,"" but rather 
as a result of the participant’s incapacity to 
organize 
arguments 
rationally. 
This 
demonstrates that the participant did not 
exercise sufficient care when collecting the 
propositions into writing form. In written 
communication, 
pre-adolescents 
make 
assertions based on what is known (Chetia, 
2013; Karadeniz, 2017). As a result, the logical 
consistency of the statements expressed does 
not appear to be a big concern for them. That is, 
the expression of propositions in written form is 
prioritized by the participants rather than the 
logical relations between propositions that are 
built in their essays.  
The 
""this/these"" belongs to the demonstrative 
category, which is frequently utilized in the 
participants’ essays as a marker of propositional 
relations. Deictic ""this/these"" is a word that 
appears earlier in language learning and is 
frequently encountered in children’s speech. 
According to the literature, toddlers as young as 
two and a half years old are already capable of 
producing deictic terms such as here, this, and 
that while communicating (Rodrigo et al., 
2004). This shows that the term ""this/these"" was 
acquired naturally by the study’s participants. 
As a result, when the participants communicate 
in writing or vocally, the word ""this/these"" is 
readily accessible in their memory. In other 
words, once the participants have mentioned 
specific items in a variety of propositions in 
their writing, it is possible that they will simply 
utilize the proximal demonstrative ""this/these""

  
to refer to these objects, as the term ""this/these"" 
is already stored in their long term memory. 
Along with the demonstrative pronouns 
this/these, that/those, and the, there are also 
combined demonstrative pronouns here, around 
the area and there. The demonstrative pronoun 
""the"" belongs to the group of combined 
demonstrative pronouns that refer to a location 
based on its form. Alwi et al. (2003) imply that 
the Indonesian pronouns for location are here, 
there, and there (far away). The use of 
combined demonstrative pronouns by the 
study’s 
as 
an 
intratextual 
antecedent designation is anaphoric. This 
demonstrates that the participants frequently 
employ 
a 
combination 
of 
pronoun references to refer to nouns (locations) 
in preceding statements. 
The findings of this study reveal that the 
participants’ use of combined demonstrative 
pronouns as indicators of propositional links 
varies significantly. The demonstrative pronoun 
""here"" is one of the five most often used 
pronouns by participants, along with ""there”, 
""around the area,"" and ""there."" Because they 
referred to previously acquired deictic words, 
the 
utilized 
combined 
pronouns 
as 
propositional 
relation markers in a variety of ways. 
According to language acquisition theory, 
children begin using deictics of the form ah, eh, 
or da during the early stages of word 
development, and by the age of two and a half, 
deictic words such as here and there appear in 
children’s language (Rodrigo et al., 2004). 
The objective of the participants’ essay 
writing also influence their employment of 
diverse combined demonstratives. Due to the 
fact that each participant prefers to write a non-
person description, they jot down words 
relating to visual things in the school setting. 
The participants wrote essays about the school 
environment. As a result, they frequently 
utilized 
spatial 
or 
mixed 
pronouns in their writing to convey the location 
of the place they are referring to. This 
demonstrates that the participants’ use of 
pronouns 
as 
a 
sign 
of 
propositional relations is very contextual. This 
conclusion supports Muşlu (2015) assertion that 
deixis 
(pronominal 
demonstrativa) 
is 
a 
linguistic technique that expresses the link 
between 
language 
and 
situation. 
Deictis 
establishes a connection between speech and 
time, place, or event. 
 
CONCLUSIONS 
 
Based on the explanation above, it is 
concluded that the propositions presented in the 
essays written by junior high school students 
involve markers of reference relations as a 
means of binding between one proposition and 
another. The participants identified three 
categories of reference words as propositional 
relation 
markers: 
third 
person 
pronouns, 
nonperson 
pronouns, 
and 
pronouns. Students from SMP Negeri 1 
Balikpapan commonly show their strengths and 
shortcomings in relating propositions to the 
reference system in written language using the 
three reference relation markers. The third 
person pronoun was effectively used by the 
participants to maintain the coherence and 
consistency of two propositions. However, 
because the participants frequently wrote non-
person descriptions, the variance in the form 
and percentage of pronouns in participant 
essays is limited. 
On the one hand, the participants’ use of 
the non-person pronoun ""its"" contributes to the 
cohesive and coherent nature of their writings; 
on the other hand, their usage of ""its"" produces 
a double meaning, disrupting the relationship 
between propositions. In comparison to the 
demonstrative pronoun ""its,"" the derived 
demonstrative pronoun ""the"" was found to be 
overused in a variety of propositions, resulting 
in redundant references. Meanwhile, the basic 
demonstrative pronoun ""this/these"" found in the 
students’ essays could not maintain the 
cohesiveness and coherence of propositions 
because the sequence of premises was not 
logical. Finally, and perhaps most intriguingly, 
nearly all participants utilized a combination of 
demonstrative pronouns in a variety of forms. 
The findings of this study indicate that 
teachers must take an active role in developing 
students’ written language awareness through 
literacy and writing practices. Additionally, 
teachers must clarify the principles governing 
the use of cohesion devices in written 
communication by exposing students to reading 
resources on the use of references as markers of 
relationships between propositions in written 
language. Second, textbook authors for junior

 
 
high school students should employ color 
highlighting to indicate reference related 
markers 
in 
their 
textbooks. 
Authors 
of 
textbooks might emphasize the forms and 
purposes of relation markers. Highlighting can 
be accomplished by assigning specific colors to 
the forms of reference relation markers, such as 
blue for personal pronoun references and red 
for non-personal pronoun references. Students 
will eventually get an understanding of 
reference forms as markers of propositional 
relations in written language in this manner.","The purpose of this study was to evaluate the use of reference as markers of propositional relations in essays written by junior high school students. This study employed a qualitative method in data collection and data analysis. The population and research samples were 94 eighth-grade students from SMP Negeri 1 in Balikpapan, Indonesia, ranging in age from 13 to 14. Data collection in this research was carried out using the listening method after the essay as a source of research data obtained from the research sample.The data analysis in this study consisted of three stages that were completed interactively: data reduction, data display, and conclusion drawing. This study suggest that participants utilized three distinct kinds of reference to denote propositional relations in their essays: third-person pronoun, non-person pronoun, and demonstrative pronoun. The third person pronoun was found to be widely used but did not vary significantly among participants. Meanwhile, participants’ usage of non-person pronouns resulted in numerous interpretations, and it was discovered that derived demonstrative pronouns were overused. These findings demonstrate the participants’ strengths and shortcomings in using reference to connect one proposition to another."
"MANIFESTATION OF INNER PEACE VALUES 
INDONESIAN TEXTBOOKS: RELEVANCE AND IMPLICATIONS 
ON THE DEVELOPMENT OF PEACE-BASED TEXTBOOKS  
Dedi Risaldi, Yuni Pratiwi, Kusubakti Andajani 
1;,2,3 Universitas Negeri Malang 
1,2,3 Jl. Ambarawa No.5 Gedung D14-18, Sumbersari, Kec. Lowokwaru, Kota Malang, Jawa Timur   
 
Article History:  
Submitted: 3 May 2024; Revised: 30 July 2024, Accepted: 31 July 2024 
 
 
RETORIKA: Jurnal Bahasa, Sastra dan Pengajarannya under 
 Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License. 
 
 
Abstract: This study aims to determine the values of peace contained in Indonesian language 
textbooks and the relevance and implications for the development of peace-based textbooks. The 
method used is a qualitative research method with an analytical descriptive approach. The data 
used is in the form of words, pictures and not in the form of a collection of numbers. The data 
source for this research is the Indonesian language textbooks of the independent curriculum. Data 
collection technique is library technique. Fund analysis was carried out using the method of 
content analysis or content analysis. The results of the study show that there are four values of 
peace contained in the Indonesian language textbooks of the independence curriculum. The four 
values are the value of self-acceptance, the value of not being prejudiced, the value of 
understanding conflict, and the value of diversity. Relevance and implications for the development 
of textbooks are needed to support learning and provide knowledge from an early age about the 
Indonesian language and ways to solve peace problems. 
 
Keywords: value of peace, textbook, Indonesian, relevance 
 
The value of peace is very important in 
creating peace. The implementation of peace 
values in schools, especially in learning, is an 
important factor as the main pillar for fighting 
conflicts that occur in the school environment 
and in the general community. Implementation 
in the world of education is not just teaching but 
is a process for a nation or state to provide 
guidance and develop self-awareness (Andari & 
Suwanda, 2021). Education has a very big role 
and contribution to the progress of a nation. 
Implementation of these peace values can be 
done by integrating with other fields of science. 
The field of science that is one of the choices for 
integration is Indonesian. Through educational 
institutions and schools, the government can 
overcome or prevent actions that violate the 
value of peace. By using integrated learning as a 
forum, it can become a recommendation in 
overcoming peace problems (Azhar, et al., 2020). 
Indonesian is a learning that cannot be separated 
from its text-based nature. Learning Indonesian 
is literacy learning for various communication 
purposes 
in 
a 
socio-cultural 
context. 
Implementation of the basic values of peace can 
provide 
positive 
results 
for 
the 
younger 
generation to better understand the importance 
of peace apart from tolerance (Annisa & Habiby, 
2024). Learning Indonesian tests language, 
literature 
and 
thinking 
skills. 
Learning

 
 
is 
useful 
for 
improving 
understanding and communicating well and 
correctly, both verbally and in writing. Learning 
Indonesian also has the aim of improving 
thinking and reasoning power in order to sharpen 
insight and knowledge (Rosanti, et. al., 2020). 
The peace values initiated by Lincoln and 
Amalee contained 12 values in the Peace 
Generation Module: 12 Basic Values of Peace 
(Lincoln & Amalee, 2010). Describes the 12 
peace values into three main groups. (1) A very 
noble goal for creating peace is to make peace 
with oneself. But to be the first to bring peace is 
a higher honor. Before becoming an agent of 
peace, someone who wants to bring peace must 
first make improvements within themselves. At 
this moment, embracing oneself and distancing 
oneself from prejudice are the two principles that 
shape making peace with oneself. The first steps 
towards achieving peace are these two ideals. 
The purpose of prejudice is to evaluate 
someone's attitude as quickly as possible without 
considering the opinions of other parties. (2) 
Obstacles to peace implies that the obstacles to 
the realization of peace from the Peace 
Generation were also adopted by the Mahabbah 
Institute for Peace and Goodness, expressed as 5 
values of peace. The five values of peace are 
group 
differences, 
ethnicity, 
religious 
differences, sexual disparities and inequality in 
economic status. (3) The path to peace implies 
that 
the 
development 
of 
harmonious 
relationships is the product of hard work. In this 
third section, the route to peace is a strategy or 
pattern to continually increase one's capacity for 
logic and problem solving. If one could learn 
certain important talents that peace agents must 
possess, building peace would be simpler. There 
are five qualities that shape the path to peace: 
accepting variation, respecting disagreement, 
rejecting violence, admitting mistakes, and 
showing forgiveness. 
In the independent curriculum Indonesian 
language learning outcomes issued by the Head 
of the Educational Standards, Curriculum and 
Assessment 
Agency 
of 
the 
of 
Education, Culture, Research and Technology 
number 008/KR/2022, it is explained that 
students will have the language skills to 
communicate and reason in accordance with the 
objectives, context social, academic and the 
world of work. Students are able to synthesize 
ideas and opinions from various sources and are 
active in expressing opinions and making 
presentations. The government always makes 
various efforts to improve the quality of 
education. One of the efforts made by the 
government is improving the existing education 
curriculum. 
The 
aim 
of 
improving 
the 
educational curriculum is to create an advanced 
and qualified generation that keeps up with the 
times. Textbooks are teaching materials in 
certain fields of study as standard books 
compiled by experts in those fields to create 
instructional aims and objectives that are 
equipped with teaching suggestions that are 
harmonious and easy to understand by users. It is 
hoped that the use of textbooks can support 
learning both in schools and universities. 
Some research on the values of peace can 
already be found. Research on peace values is 
studied from several perspectives including, 
education 
and 
multi-dimensional 
curriculum (Nurwanto & Habiby, 2020), peace 
education based on local wisdom (Hasudungan 
et al., 2020), image media on peace dynamics 
material (Yusmianti & Dewi, 2022). Based on 
these developments, research on the value of 
peace in Indonesian language textbooks for the 
independent curriculum has never been carried 
out. Therefore, it is important to implement 
peace values in Indonesian language textbooks 
for the independent curriculum. 
This research uses the peace value theory 
by Lincoln & Amalee (2010). The peace value 
consists of 12 values which are grouped into 
three categories. These three categories are 
described as follows. (1) Making peace with 
oneself is intended to create peace with a very 
noble goal. However, it is more noble to be a 
pioneer in creating peace. A person who wants 
to bring about peace must first improve from 
within himself before becoming an agent of 
peace. At this point, being at peace with oneself 
is divided into two values, namely accepting 
oneself and not having bad prejudices. These 
two values are the first steps that a person must 
have to realize peace. Not being prejudiced aims 
to assess a person's attitude as early as possible 
without consideration from various parties. (2) 
Obstacles to peace implies that the obstacles to 
the realization of peace according to the Peace 
Generation which was also adopted by the 
Mahabbah Institute for Peace and Goodness are 
expressed as five values of peace. The five 
values 
of 
are 
tribalism, 
religious

  
differences, gender differences, economic status 
differences and group differences. (3) The path 
to peace implies that the creation of peaceful 
relations is the result of efforts that are not easy. 
In this third part, the path to peace is a path or 
pattern to continually hone your reasoning 
abilities and understanding of a problem. Peace 
will be easier to create if someone is able to 
master certain skills that are very important for 
peace agents to have. The path to peace is 
divided into five values, namely understanding 
mistakes, 
