Discussion 
 
Based on the research results that have been 
presented, there are two main points of 
discussion that will be explained, namely (1) the 
values 
of 
in 
textbooks for the independent curriculum, and (2) 
the relevance of peace values in the development 
of learning textbooks. The discussion is 
examined by linking theory and research. The 
following discussion is explained. 
From the analysis carried out, the values of 
peace that appear in the Indonesian language 
textbooks for the independent curriculum are (1) 
accepting oneself, (2) not having negative 
prejudices, (3) understanding conflict, and (4) 
understanding diversity. The peace values found 
are based on the book Peace Generation: 12 
Basic Values of Peace by Lincoln and Amalee. 
Generally learning about the value of peace is 
found in Citizenship Education subjects. Peace 
education is a step that must be taken to 
harmonize human life (Gross, 2017). Learning 
about peace education is based on the aim of 
providing knowledge, skills and attitudes so as 
to be able to foster good relations in society 
(Lerner, 2018). In Indonesian language learning 
outcomes, the independent curriculum explains 
that students have the language skills to 
communicate and reason in accordance with 
objectives, social, academic contexts and the 
world of work. In the independent curriculum 
too, there is a Pancasila student profile program 
which of course we can also include the 
cultivation of peace values which have become 
an international issue. 
The use of the value of peace in this 
research serves to see whether the independent 
curriculum 
textbooks 
that 
are 
currently 
distributed have instilled the value of peace. As 
far as we have observed, no other research has 
been found that examines the value of peace in 
Indonesian language textbooks. In the world of 
education, especially in Indonesia, which has 
used an independent curriculum, it would be 
good for educators to be able to create a 
textbook which contains the existing values of 
peace. These existing peace values can be 
integrated with existing texts in Indonesian

 
 
(Lewsader, 2017). The peace values studied in 
this research aim to build positive social 
interactions. Building positive social interactions 
including mutual respect and high tolerance 
(Akbar et al., 2018). 
Instilling peaceful values is important to 
create peace in a region. Knowledge about peace 
is provided with various alternatives for 
cognitive understanding of the causes of 
violence and provides students with some 
knowledge about peace. The main issue of peace 
is maintaining, creating and building peace. In 
textbooks 
published 
by 
the 
of 
Education, Culture, Research and Technology of 
the Republic of Indonesia, especially in 
Indonesian language subjects, there is still very 
little attention to the realm of understanding the 
value of peace. The value of peace is a world-
centric issue that has become a topic of much 
discussion. Learning about the value of peace is 
very important for the nation's future generations 
so that they can overcome the peace problems 
they will face. The peace problems they will face 
are not only world peace problems, they can 
overcome even smaller peace problems in the 
environment around them if they understand the 
value of peace. 
In the textbooks in circulation, especially in 
the independent curriculum, only a handful of 
peace values are contained therein. Apart from 
that, the textbook does not provide a specific 
explanation about peace. The importance of 
knowing the value of peace should be known 
from an early age by the younger generation. 
This is important because knowing about the 
values of peace can minimize problems that can 
cause division. It is not only civic education that 
must discuss the value of peace. However, 
learning Indonesian can also be done using an 
integrative approach. An integrative approach is 
used by combining Indonesian language subjects 
with other fields of science such as the value of 
peace. Instilling peace values in the development 
of learning textbooks can have implications so 
that the younger generation not only learns the 
values of peace from citizenship education 
subjects but can also be obtained in other 
learning such as Indonesian (Nurwanto et al., 
2015). Indonesian language learning as we know 
is text-based learning. Text-based learning 
provides students with the opportunity to acquire 
good declarative and procedural knowledge 
(Pratiwi et al., 2023; Wuryaningrum et al., 2020). 
Texts presented in Indonesian can be integrated 
with peace values such as including peace 
themes in these texts. This can enable students as 
the younger generation to understand well 
through texts in Indonesian language learning. 
This is important because with text-based 
learning, students can understand and instill 
these values. Relevant research conducted by 
Zahro et al. (2022) regarding the development of 
an attitude of tolerance through children's stories 
as a medium shows that the children's stories 
that are developed can be a guide for producing 
other children's stories from various points of 
view as a means of instilling morals. 
In developing textbooks, integration of 
peace values with Indonesian language learning 
can be provided by using the theme of peace 
values in texts in Indonesian. When compared 
with Ezeoba (2012) research which examined 
strategies for increasing peace education into the 
junior high school social studies curriculum. The 
findings explain strategies such as peace 
integration which contains material such as 
cultural similarities, human rights, hostage 
taking, global challenges and others. The 
development of teaching materials is very 
important because teaching materials are a 
component that plays an important role in the 
learning process (Pratama et al., 2016). The role 
of teaching materials is considered very 
important because it makes it easier for teachers 
to carry out the teaching and learning process 
(Azizan et al., 2021). Apart from that, teaching 
materials can be an alternative for teachers to 
create learning that is creative and fun and in 
accordance 
with 
current 
developments 
(Luciandika & Andajani, 2020). 
 
CONCLUSIONS 
 
The peace values found in this research 
consist of four values. The four values of peace 
are accepting oneself, not having negative 
prejudices, 
and 
diversity. 
Instilling 
peaceful 
values is very important in learning not only in 
specific subjects but can also be integrated into 
other subjects such as text-based Indonesian. 
Knowledge about peace is provided with various 
alternatives for cognitive understanding of the 
causes of violence and provides students with 
some knowledge about peace. The main issue of 
peace is maintaining, creating and building

  
peace. In developing textbooks, it is hoped that 
attention will be given so that a platform can be 
provided so that in the development of textbooks, 
especially in other subjects, they can be 
integrated with peace themes so that students as 
the younger generation can be prepared and have 
more knowledge to overcome peace problems.","This study aims to determine the values of peace contained in Indonesian language textbooks and the relevance and implications for the development of peace-based textbooks. The method used is a qualitative research method with an analytical descriptive approach. The data used is in the form of words, pictures and not in the form of a collection of numbers. The data source for this research is the Indonesian language textbooks of the independent curriculum. Data collection technique is library technique. Fund analysis was carried out using the method of content analysis or content analysis. The results of the study show that there are four values of peace contained in the Indonesian language textbooks of the independence curriculum. The four values are the value of self-acceptance, the value of not being prejudiced, the value of understanding conflict, and the value of diversity. Relevance and implications for the development of textbooks are needed to support learning and provide knowledge from an early age about the Indonesian language and ways to solve peace problems."
"SYMBOLIC MEANING IN THE MOVIE DUA GARIS BIRU THE 
WORK OF GINATRI S. NOER AND THE INTERNALIZATION  
OF SEX EDUCATION  
  
Andi Tenri Sua, Daud Rodi Palimbong, Andi Nurhabibi Marwil, Antika Utami Putri, Elihami 
1,3,4 Universitas Muhammadiyah Bone 
2 Universitas Kristen Indonesia Toraja 
5 Universitas Muhammadiyah Enrekang 
1,3,4 Jl. Biru, Kec. Tanete Riattang, Kabupaten Bone, Sulawesi Selatan 
2 Jl. Nusantara No.12, Kel. Bombongan, Kec. Makale, Kabupaten Tana Toraja, Sulawesi Selatan 
5 Jl. Jenderal Sudirman, Galonta, Kec. Enrekang, Kabupaten Enrekang, Sulawesi Selatan 
 
Article History:  
Submitted: 28 November 2024; Revised: 17 July 2024, Accepted: 24 July 2024 
 
 
RETORIKA: Jurnal Bahasa, Sastra dan Pengajarannya under 
 Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License. 
 
 
Abstract: The research aims to find out the symbolic meaning of the film Dua Garis Biru by 
Ginatri S. Noer, the impact of early marriage and how to internalize sex education in the younger 
generation. This research uses a qualitative descriptive research design using Roland Barthes's 
Semiotic Analysis Method with connotation and denotation meanings. The subject of this study is 
the film Dua Garis Biru, with the object of the research is the symbolic meaning that is found in 
the film Dua Garis Biru Ginatri S.Noer's work (Bara and Bima) as the internalization of Sex 
Education in the younger generation. Data is collected through, observations, documentation and 
interviews using Rolland Barthes' semiotic analysis that emphasizes the observation of phenomena 
and requires strong instincts. Data analysis phases include data reduction, data presentation, and 
conclusion. As  for the scientific implications that can be concluded through this research that the 
film. The film Dua Garis Biru portrays the consequences faced by two young individuals after 
engaging in sexual intercourse, significantly impacting their lives. It underscores the critical role 
of parents in their children's lives, particularly in communicating sexual information. The findings 
suggest that films with relevant content can effectively address and promote an understanding of 
sexual health issues among young audiences. This study contributes to the understanding of sex 
education in movies, illustrating how cinematic narratives can serve as educational tools for sexual 
health. 
 
Keywords: symbolic meaning, sex education, semiotics 
 
Language is a complex system of sound 
communication, utilizing agreed-upon sound 
marks that convey specific meanings (Tanwete, 
& Kombinda, 2020). Linguistics, the scientific 
study of language, can be broadly divided into 
internal and external linguistics (Muhassin. 
(2017). Internal linguistics focuses on the 
structure and function of language itself, such as 
syntax, phonetics, and semantics. External 
linguistics, on the other hand, examines the 
relationship between language and external

 
 
factors, 
including 
social, 
cultural, 
and 
psychological influences.  
This study is concerned with external 
linguistics, exploring how language interacts 
with various external elements. Specifically, it 
aims to investigate the sociocultural dimensions 
of language use, examining how linguistic 
practices are shaped by and reflect social 
identities, cultural norms, and communicative 
contexts. By focusing on external aspects of 
language, this research seeks to contribute to a 
deeper understanding of the dynamic interplay 
between language and society, highlighting the 
significance of external influences in the 
evolution and functioning of language systems.  
Language serves as a systematic means of 
sound-based communication, utilizing sound 
symbols that carry meaning through mutual 
agreement (Hartman & Paradis, 2023).  
This research focuses on external language, 
specifically semiotics. Etymologically, the term 
semiotics comes from the Greek word semion, 
which translates to ""sign"", referring to the 
representation of an object or name. Semiotics 
encompasses the study of signs and symbols, 
which 
are 
essential 
components 
of 
communication traditions. It examines the theory 
of how signs represent various entities, including 
objects, ideas, situations, emotions, and more. 
Humans frequently employ signs to refer to 
objects, highlighting the integral role of 
semiotics. The findings from the study on Dua 
Garis Biru highlight the film's use of metaphoric 
expressions to convey complex messages about 
sexual health and responsibility. This aligns with 
Charles Sanders Peirce's semiotic theory, which 
emphasizes the role of signs in communication. 
According to Peirce, a sign consists of a 
representamen (the perceivable part), an object 
(the concept it represents), and an interpretant 
(the meaning derived from the sign). In Dua 
Garis Biruthese elements are employed to 
represent and communicate the consequences of 
teenage pregnancy and the importance of sex 
education. The representamen in the film 
includes visual and narrative elements, the object 
is the real-life issue of teenage pregnancy, and 
the interpretant is the moral and educational 
messages perceived by the audience. 
One new insight from this study is the 
integration of cultural context within the 
metaphoric expressions. While Peirce’s theory 
provides a framework for understanding signs 
universally, 
the 
film’s 
culturally 
specific 
narrative offers a fresh perspective on how 
metaphors and symbols can be tailored to 
resonate more deeply with local audiences. This 
cultural specificity adds a unique layer to the 
metaphoric expressions in the film, making the 
educational messages more impactful for the 
Indonesian audience. 
Additionally, 
Sperber’s 
explanation 
of 
symbolic interaction enhances the understanding 
of the film’s metaphoric expressions. Sperber 
posits that symbolic interaction is more than just 
a code; it is an implicit rule-following process 
that makes human experience meaningful. This 
theory supports the idea that the metaphors in 
Dua Garis Biru are not just tools for social 
communication but are deeply embedded in the 
viewers' mental frameworks, enriching their 
understanding and emotional engagement with 
the film. 
The study aligns with previous research that 
highlights the role of media in sex education. For 
example, underscores the importance of sex 
education in the digital age, where films and 
other media play a crucial role in shaping young 
people's understanding of sexual health. This 
finding is consistent with international research, 
such as (Mellanby et al., 2001), which supports 
the effectiveness of media in delivering sex 
education messages. 
However,  Dua Garis Biru offers a unique 
contribution by focusing on the cultural aspects 
of Indonesian society, something that is not 
extensively covered in previous international 
studies. The film navigates the cultural norms 
and societal expectations specific to Indonesia, 
which may include the value placed on virginity 
and the roles of parents in guiding their children. 
This cultural context adds a unique dimension to 
the metaphoric expressions in the film, making 
the educational content more relatable and 
effective for the local audience (Toor, 2012). 
While previous research primarily examines 
media’s role in sex education within Western 
contexts, this study provides an important 
perspective from a non-Western context. The 
cultural nuances in Dua Garis Biru highlight the 
necessity of considering cultural specificity 
when evaluating the impact of media on sex 
education. This focus on cultural context offers 
new insights into how metaphoric expressions 
can be adapted to different cultural settings to 
enhance their effectiveness, (Kohler et al., 2008).

  
In conclusion, the study of Dua Garis Biru 
extends previous research by demonstrating the 
importance of culturally contextualized media in 
sex education. The unique integration of cultural 
symbols and narrative techniques enriches the 
theoretical understanding of semiotics and 
metaphoric expression, emphasizing the need to 
consider cultural specificity in educational media 
research (Huber & Firmin, 2014). 
Against this background, it is important to 
conduct in-depth research into the film Dua 
Garis Biru to uncover its symbolic meaning as 
an internalisation of sex education for the 
younger generation, especially in the 5.0 era. 
Previous studies have explored various aspects 
of this topic. For example, Hanifa (2020) 
research found that the film had a moderate 
influence on teenage promiscuity behaviour, 
with a ratio of 0.420. Another study titled by 
Walker, (2001) found that the film influenced 
teenagers' awareness of open relationships by 
16.7%, with other factors playing a greater role 
(Walker, 2001). 
The innovation in this research lies in 
revealing 
the 
denotative 
and 
connotative 
meanings of the film Dua Garis Biru as the 
internalization of sex education in the younger 
generation using semiotic theory. It is hoped that 
this study will serve as a tool to convey various 
messages to the general public through the 
medium of storytelling. Additionally, it aims to 
be understood as a medium of expression for 
artists and filmmakers to express their ideas 
(Martin et al., 2020). 
Ginatri S. Noer's film Dua Garis Biru 
presents a social reality that underscores the 
importance of sexual education for adolescents. 
The film’s message is relevant to teenagers, 
adults, teachers, parents, and families. This 
research will analyze the connotations and 
denotations present in the film using Roland 
Barthes' semiotic analysis. 
 
METHOD 
 
This research uses qualitative methods 
using Rolland Barthes' semiotic analysis that 
emphasizes observation of phenomena and 
requires strong instincts. The subject of this 
article is the film Dua Garis Biru, in which 
researchers attempt to uncover the symbolic 
meaning of the internalization of sex education 
in the younger generation. Through this research, 
the symbolic meaning of the narrative, the 
conversation and the meaning of signs in the 
film will be presented by the way of watching 
carefully and repeatedly, then recorded then 
taken some scans (scenes) with the technique of 
screen prints. Next, the meaning of denotation 
and connotation will be explained according to 
Roland Barthes' semiotic analysis as well as the 
impact of early marriage and how to internalize 
sex education on the younger generation.  
In this research uses a qualitative approach. 
The collection of data in this study is twofold: (1) 
primary data obtained from the movie Dua Garis 
Biru watching, recording, and screenshots 
containing symbols, (2) secondary data is data 
obtaining 
through 
literature 
that 
supports 
primary 
information, 
such 
as 
articles, 
dictionaries, internet and books related to 
research. (3) Interviews, in order to obtain 
information in the form of oral statements 
concerning early marriage carried out by source 
(Thammaraksa et al., 2014). The source of data 
in this research is the symbolic meaning of 
speeches, conversations as well as the meaning 
of signs found in the movie Dua Garis Biru. The 
data analysis technique in the film Dua Garis 
Biru uses a qualitative descriptive approach with 
stages, 
first: 
perform 
observations 
and 
observations by the way of watching, observing 
scenes, background places, symbols, as well the 
characters in the movies Two blue line, second 
recording, selecting visuals or clips of scenes in 
the films Dua Garis Biru, Third, conducting 
documentation studies, i.e. studying various 
literature relevant to the research and results of 
the research. 
 
