when they were born. Dara tries to convince 
Bima that this is the best way for the future of 
both of them. Dara says it's not easy to raise a 
child, especially at an immature age. From the 
scene it can be concluded that there is no 
certainty in marriage even if there is love in it. 
Important things like building a household, 
raising children, finding a job, all of them aren't 
easy. From some scenes, it seems that Dara 
always sees her parents arguing about little 
things, even Bima, so Dara decides maybe this is 
the best way for her future, especially for her 
son's future . 
At Bone Province of South Sulawesi, in 
2021 from January to December by the Ministry 
of Religion of Bone District shows that the total 
number of marriages under the age of 19 years is 
quite high. The total is 14 men and 48 women. 
There are many efforts made by the 
government to prevent early marriages in Bone 
district, 
among 
them 
the 
campaign 
and 
socialization by the Bone District Children's 
Forum 
under 
the 
umbrella 
of 
Women's 
Empowerment and Child Protection to bridge 
communication and interaction between the 
government and children in order to fulfill the 
right of participation of children. As for the 
activities carried out by Bone County Child 
Forum on October 15, 2017 among them 
socialization 
on 
child 
age 
marriage 
and 
socialization of the importance of physical 
health 
promoted 
by 
the 
Department 
of 
Population 
Control 
and 
Planned 
Families 
(DP2KB that used to be BKKBN). Then on 
December 
1, 
implemented 
a 
joint 
declaration of child marriage prevention that was 
carried out in front of the Department of 
Nutrition Security Cabinet Bone. This activity 
aims to convey the dangers and consequences of 
early marriage. On Saturday, December 22nd, 
the activities with the theme “Joint Declaration 
on the Prevention and Termination of Child 
Marriages” were reopened at the PKK Bone  
building, with the aim of preventing and ending 
child marriages. On Sunday, July 25, 2021, 
exactly at Watampone Green Epicentrum again 
held the declaration of “Children's Marriage 
Abrogation” that there have been 6,237 cases of 
PUA (Childhood Marriage) in Bone district in 
2020. The activity begins with an education on 
the impact of PUA on parents and children and 
also provides a brief education about the 
importance of PHBS in the new normal era. 
 
Internalising Sex Education In The Young 
Generation 
Internalization is the final stage of man's 
embodiment of the social reality around him. At 
this stage, humans absorb objective things and 
then subjectively realize them. Internalization 
lasts 
a 
lifetime 
through 
socialization. 
Socialization is not just guidance but a process 
of internalizing values. At the stage of 
internalization, each human has a different 
dimension of absorption. There 
is more 
absorption of external or otherwise aspects that 
can be acquired by individuals through the 
process of primary socialization (the first and 
primary processes experienced by individuals 
within the family environment) and secondary 
socialization. 
(Advanced 
socialization 
after 
primary or common socialization is also called 
socialization outside the family environment). 
The film Dua Garis Biru by Ginatri S. Noer 
presents the internalization of sex education in 
between. 
 During 02.39-04.30 depicted when Dara 
and Bima were having a marriage. This scene 
shows 
that 
adolescent 
dating 
behavior 
sometimes crosses boundaries. Dating teenagers 
like a secluded place away from crowds. It's an 
opportunity for them to get rid of their lusts. 
Therefore, important sexual education is taught 
in schools as a provision for adolescents to 
maintain cohesion and boundaries between the 
opposite sexes. 
During 
19.11-36.14-46.42-1.24.28 
is 
described the impact experienced by the main

 
 
character as a result of what he has done. Dua 
Garis Biru are a sign on the test pack that 
indicates someone is pregnant. Freedom of 
association among teenagers can have a negative 
impact on women. Teenage pregnancies are 
potentially prone to miscarriage and even death 
due to their physical and mental impairment.   
During 1.34.58 described the importance of 
sexual supervision and education in children. 
The Dua Garis Biru convey an important 
message to parents to always give advice, 
supervision, and sexual education to their 
children so that they do not fall into the wrong 
relationship. However, this is rarely done in 
Indonesia. Talking about sexual education is still 
taboo in society. Therefore, socialization related 
to sexual education should be done from society 
to schools.  
At the duration of 14.55 depicted a poster of 
the reproductive instrument in the school's UKS. 
The poster shown in the film Dua Garis Biru 
conveys about reproductive health. These 
posters are not just an ornament; they mean that 
sexual education for teenagers is vital.   
The symbolic meaning in Dua Garis Biru 
can be deeply understood through the lens of 
semiotic theory, which examines how signs and 
symbols communicate meanings. According to 
Charles Sanders Peirce's semiotic theory, a sign 
consists of a representamen (the form of the 
sign), an object (the content or concept it 
represents), and an interpretant (the meaning 
derived by the observer). In Dua Garis 
Biruvarious signs and symbols are used to 
represent the consequences of teenage pregnancy 
and the importance of sex education. The film 
uses representamen in the form of visual and 
narrative elements, objects as the situations and 
characters, and interpretants as the moral and 
educational messages perceived by the audience. 
 
Discussion 
 
The film Dua Garis Biru, directed by Gina 
S. Noer, explores significant symbolic meanings 
related to the challenges and responsibilities that 
come with teenage pregnancy. Through its 
narrative and character development, the film 
underscores the repercussions of early sexual 
activity and highlights the critical role of 
parental guidance and communication in sexual 
education. The symbolic elements in the movie 
serve to illustrate the complex emotions and 
societal pressures faced by the young couple, 
providing a vivid portrayal of their journey from 
innocence to accountability  (Ismail et al., 2015). 
The findings of the study suggest that the 
movie 
effectively 
uses 
symbolism 
to 
communicate important messages about sexual 
health 
and 
responsibility. 
The 
characters' 
experiences symbolize the broader issues of 
teenage pregnancy, societal judgment, and the 
lack of comprehensive sex education. This 
symbolic representation helps to internalize the 
lessons of sexual education among young 
viewers by making the consequences of their 
actions more relatable and impactful. In 
summary, Dua Garis Biru demonstrates the 
potential of films to convey critical social 
messages and influence the understanding and 
behavior of young audiences regarding sexual 
health (Lindberg & Kantor, 2022). The study 
highlights 
the 
importance 
of 
integrating 
symbolic storytelling in media as a tool for 
educating and shaping the perspectives of the 
younger generation on sensitive topics like sex 
education (Trudell, 2017). The findings of the 
study on Dua Garis Biru reveal the film's 
effectiveness in using symbolic elements to 
communicate critical messages about sexual 
health and responsibility (Irvine, 2004). By 
depicting 
the 
consequences 
of 
teenage 
pregnancy through relatable characters and 
situations, the movie serves as a powerful 
medium for internalizing sex education among 
young audiences (Irvine, 2000). The symbolic 
meanings embedded in the film, such as the 
representation 
of 
innocence 
lost, 
societal 
judgment, and the importance of parental 
guidance, resonate deeply with viewers, making 
the 
educational 
message 
more 
impactful, 
(Measor et al., 2012). 
For the study of metaphoric expression, 
these findings underscore the significance of 
symbolic and metaphorical storytelling in 
conveying complex social issues. The film's 
ability to use metaphors and symbols to 
represent real-life challenges and emotions 
enhances the audience's understanding and 
empathy. 
It 
illustrates 
how 
metaphoric 
expressions can bridge the gap between abstract 
concepts and tangible experiences, making the 
lessons 
more 
accessible 
and 
memorable, 
(Lindberg & Kantor, 2022). 
From visual analysis with connotations and 
denotations, a sign of sex education in early

  
pregnancy emerges. The importance of sex 
education is to prevent children from engaging 
in inappropriate sexual activities, children are 
not drunk when entering puberty, and children's 
awareness to take care of their reproductive 
organs and prevent (Holzner & Oetomo, 2004). 
Among the results of the research on the impact 
of early marriage shown in the film Dua Garis 
Biru are: impaired education, complications of 
pregnancy, unexpected pregnancies due to lack 
of knowledge about sex education, economic or 
financial problems, and) divorce. 
Can we associate with the problems 
experienced by married sources under the age of 
19 or carrying out early marriage seen from the 
point of view of the impediment of education 
makes married couples young, not able to 
continue 
their 
further 
education? 
Psychologically or mentally unprepared to face 
pregnancy and not ready to assume the role of 
mother or head of household. Then from the 
economic side, the lack of income and the 
difficulty to find a job as well as from the social 
side can increase the incidence of divorce, due to 
the emotional liabilities of early marriage 
teenagers and their unripe way of thinking, 
(Talib et al., 2012).  
The importance of sex education for the 
younger generation begins in the family 
environment. Parents and families become the 
environment that has the strongest preventive 
effort and keeps them from engaging in free 
social activities. Initially, adolescent interest in 
sexuality was self-centered, that is, focused on 
the changes that occurred in him, (Agbemenu & 
Schlenk, 2011).  
Giving 
sexual 
education 
to 
younger 
generations can improve understanding of 
sexuality in a healthy way and prevent sexual 
abuse and sexual harassment (McCann et al., 
2019). 
Giving 
education 
in 
sexual 
and 
reproductive health can help the younger 
generation to reduce the incidence of sexual 
activity, delay sexual initiation, reduce the 
frequency of unsafe sex.  (Tripathi & Sekher, 
2013), and prevent unwanted pregnancies and 
sexually transmitted infections. There 
are 
therefore a number of principles related to sex 
education that should be taught in the main 
environment of the family, among them: ethics 
asking for permission, ethic seeing; avoiding 
children from sexual stimulation, (providing 
information about marriage and sexual relations, 
preserving self-esteem, and explaining sexual 
issues openly. This finding is in line with 
research conducted by Dahlia et al. (2021) that 
the use of media is very effective in preventing 
sexual violence and can increase knowledge of 
sex education for children. 
 
CONCLUSIONS 
 
Sexuality is a very taboo thing to talk about, 
which is why movies about sexuality are very 
rare in Indonesia. Dua Garis Biru tells about the 
importance of sex education, especially the 
dangers of free sex. The two-line blue film 
released in 2019 also explains the reality of early 
marriage, which is still considered a taboo 
amongst the society. This is due to the 
environmental influence and the lack of 
communication between children and parents 
about sexual education. The film raises the 
theme of teenage pregnancies outside of 
marriage. In the film there are some implicit 
meanings that the director wants to convey to the 
audience that are not only entertaining but also 
moral and educational. 
Using Roland Barthes's denotation and 
connotation analysis, the study has found that 
today's adolescent dating style tends to slide 
towards sexual behavior expressed through 
kissing, hugging, holding hands and so on, 
leading to early marriages and extra-marital 
pregnancies that have a profound impact on her 
life, not only in terms of health but also in 
educational, 
economic 
and 
social 
terms. 
Therefore, the role of parents in children's lives 
is very important, especially in communicating 
sexual information to children.","The research aims to find out the symbolic meaning of the film Dua Garis Biru by Ginatri S. Noer, the impact of early marriage and how to internalize sex education in the younger generation. This research uses a qualitative descriptive research design using Roland Barthes's Semiotic Analysis Method with connotation and denotation meanings. The subject of this study is the film Dua Garis Biru, with the object of the research is the symbolic meaning that is found in the film Dua Garis Biru Ginatri S.Noer's work (Bara and Bima) as the internalization of Sex Education in the younger generation. Data is collected through, observations, documentation and interviews using Rolland Barthes' semiotic analysis that emphasizes the observation of phenomena and requires strong instincts. Data analysis phases include data reduction, data presentation, and conclusion. As for the scientific implications that can be concluded through this research that the film. The film Dua Garis Biru portrays the consequences faced by two young individuals after engaging in sexual intercourse, significantly impacting their lives. It underscores the critical role of parents in their children's lives, particularly in communicating sexual information. The findings suggest that films with relevant content can effectively address and promote an understanding of sexual health issues among young audiences. This study contributes to the understanding of sex education in movies, illustrating how cinematic narratives can serve as educational tools for sexual health."
"VERBAL AGGRESSION IN INDONESIAN SOCIAL MEDIA 
DISCOURSE:  A QUALITATIVE ANALYSIS OF FACEBOOK POSTS  
 
Ryan Rayhana Sofyan, Hasriani, Sakaria 
1,2,3 Fakultas Bahasa dan Sastra, Universitas Negeri Makassar 
1,2,3 Jl. Daeng Tata Raya, Makassar, Suawesi Selatan 
 
Article History:  
Submitted: 20 June 2024; Revised: 24  July 2024, Accepted: 26 July 2024 
 
 
RETORIKA: Jurnal Bahasa, Sastra dan Pengajarannya under 
 Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License. 
 
 
Abstract: This study investigates the phenomenon of verbal aggression in posts on social media 
platforms, particularly Facebook, in Indonesian language. The research applied a qualitative 
descriptive methodology to explore the ways in which verbal aggressiveness manifests in user 
conversations within a specific linguistic and cultural specific context. The analysis, based on 
Pierre Bourdieu's Symbolic Violence theory, aims to identify several types and interpretations of 
verbal aggression, including hyperbole, euphemism, dysphemism, stigmatization, and association. 
The results indicate that Indonesian Facebook users often employ these linguistic tactics to express 
aggression in a subtle or explicit manner. This study not only classifies the various forms of verbal 
aggressiveness commonly found in Indonesian Facebook conversations, but also analyzes the 
social and cultural elements that shape these interactions. The study emphasizes the significance of 
comprehending cultural subtleties in verbal aggression in digital communication, which could be 
advantageous in formulating improved social media communication rules and cultivating a more 
courteous online interaction environment. 
 
Keywords: verbal aggression, social media, discourse analysis 
 
Communication, whether written or verbal, 
is an essential need for all human beings. Social 
networking sites like Facebook have emerged as 
important platforms for communication in the 
digital 
age, 
allowing 
users 
to 
instantly 
communicate ideas, opinions, and feelings with 
a large audience.  In Indonesia, Facebook is 
widely popular, serving as a main platform for 
social interaction and information exchange 
(Patahuddin & Logan, 2019). However, the 
unregulated nature of these platforms often leads 
to the negative language, including verbal 
violence (Ferreira et al., 2020). The escalating 
issue of verbal aggression on social media is a 
cause for concern due to its potential to cause 
substantial psychological damage, destroy social 
cohesion, 
and 
create 
a 
culture 
of 
intolerance(Koller & Darida, 2020). Online 
environments magnify these interactions because 
of their extensive reach and the opportunity for 
users to remain anonymous, enabling harsh 
language to spread more easily and with less 
responsibility. Based on a recent study, hate 
speech and abusive language (HSAL) on 
Indonesian social media platforms have become 
widespread, provoking conflicts among citizens 
and frequently resulting in real negative 
consequences (Ibrohim & Budi, 2023). The

  
study emphasizes the importance of identifying 
HSAL in order to reduce these consequences and 
prevent additional damage. 
Bourdieu's theory of Symbolic Violence 
argues that language and cultural norms contain 
hidden and subtle forms of coercion, which 
sustain social hierarchies and power relations 
without explicit physical force (Jenkins, 2013). 
Verbal violence, in contrast to physical violence, 
is dependent on words and can have a more 
subtle and harmful effect, resulting in lasting 
psychological consequences such as diminished 
self-worth, heightened anxiety, and sadness 
(Harel et al., 2020).  
Research in this field have revealed various 
forms of verbal aggressiveness, such as 
hyperbole, 
euphemism, 
dysphemism, 
stigmatization, and animal association. Prior 
research explored many different aspects of 
verbal aggression. Spector et al., (2007) 
emphasizes that verbal aggression can have an 
equally damaging impact as physical violence, 
negatively affecting individuals' psychological 
well-being. Sinani (2023) further elaborates on 
this topic by categorizing specific types of verbal 
violence, including; explicit threats, public 
humiliation, and insulting comments. These 
studies highlight the widespread phenomenon of 
verbal violence and its harmful consequences. 
Kumar (2021) conducted a comprehensive 
quantitative study that investigated aggression 
on social media. The study specifically analyzed 
a multilingual dataset consisting of Facebook 
comments and tweets. The study constructed 
classifiers 
to 
identify 
aggressiveness, 
emphasizing the difficulty of achieving strong 
agreement between annotators because of the 
subjective character of aggression(Hiskes, 2019). 
study 
highlighted 
the 
necessity 
of 
automated systems for handling the extensive 
amount of content created by users(Ho, 2022). 
However, it also recognized the challenges in 
effectively detecting verbal violence due to its 
subtle and complex characteristics. 
In their study, Ferreira et al. (2020) 
examined how social ties and self-efficacy 
beliefs influence the use of harsh language on 
the internet by adolescents. Their research 
revealed that the use of aggressive language 
online is influenced by the relationships with the 
victim and other bystanders, as well as self-
efficacy views. This sheds light on the social 
dynamics 
that 
contribute 
to 
online 
aggressiveness. This study emphasized the need 
of comprehending the social and psychological 
elements that lead to verbal aggression in digital 
encounters. 
Despite thorough investigation into verbal 
aggression, there are still significant areas that 
lack information, especially when it comes to 
exchanges on social media platforms (Bykov et 
al., 2018). Many existing studies mostly examine 
broad types of verbal aggression, without in-
depth analysis of linguistic patterns and cultural 
subtleties found in various languages and 
communities(Susilo, 
2008). 
The 
distinct 
attributes of Indonesian verbal aggression in 
social 
media 
discussions 
have 
not 
been 
extensively analyzed. Although several research 
have employed qualitative methodologies to 
study verbal violence, there is a lack of 
frameworks that integrate theories of symbolic 
violence to examine the fundamental power 
dynamics and social structures that enable verbal 
aggression. Bourdieu's concept of symbolic 
violence offers a crucial perspective for 
understanding 
the 
continuation 
of 
violence on social media. 
This study distinguishes itself by examining 
verbal aggression in Indonesian social media, 
particularly on Facebook, utilizing a qualitative 
descriptive methodology and Bourdieu's theory 
of Symbolic Violence. In contrast to the earlier 
studies that frequently rely on quantitative 
methods and lack cultural context, this research 
offers a comprehensive analysis of linguistic and 
cultural subtleties in Indonesian interactions. 
 
METHOD 
 
research 
utilized 
a 
qualitative 
descriptive methodology to examine occurrences 
of verbal aggression in comments written in the 
Indonesian language on the social media 
platform Facebook. The research centers on 
comprehending the structures and significances 
of verbal aggression within the context of 
Symbolic Violence, as posited by Pierre 
Bourdieu. This study employed specific research 
design, data collection, and data analysis 
methodologies, which will be described in the 
following sections. 
The study used a qualitative descriptive 
design, which is appropriate for investigating the 
intricate and subtle characteristics of verbal 
aggression in social media conversations (Clarke

 
 
et al., 2015; Creswell, 2014; Miles & Saldana, 
2019). The study is based on the notion of 
Symbolic Violence, which offers a perspective 
to analyze the discreet and frequently subtle 
types of coercion that are present in language 
and cultural norms. The design prioritizes both 
the procedure and results of the research, with 
the 
goal 
of 
offering 
a 
comprehensive 
understanding of verbal aggression on Facebook. 
The data collecting procedures are carefully 
developed to ensure the methodical and 
complete collection of relevant information from 
Facebook. These methods consist of multiple 
stages, each designed to systematically capture 
and document occurrences of verbal aggression. 
In the initial phase, we employ a careful 
reading approach to analyze comments on 
Facebook, with a specific emphasis on topics 
that are prone to evoking resentful or violent 
comments. Comments that exhibit signs of 
verbal aggression are identified and marked for 
additional examination. We guarantee the 
evaluation of a broad range of comments in 
order to catch different manifestations of verbal 
aggressiveness. 
During 
the 
second 
phase, 
the 
documentation technique is utilized. We utilize 
smartphones to capture screenshots of the 
identified 
comments. 
Every 
screenshot 
is 
assigned 
a 
distinct 
identity 
to 
simplify 
referencing throughout the analysis stage. 
Furthermore, the situational context of each 
comment, including the post it is responding to, 
is carefully noted in order to comprehend the 
contextual circumstances around the verbal 
aggression. 
The third phase entails the utilization of the 
note-taking methodology. We transfer the 
screenshots to computers for the purpose of 
categorization and examination. Each screenshot 
is annotated with initial comments, focusing on 
important components of the verbal violence, 
such as particular words or phrases employed, 
the type of aggression, and the recipient of the 
aggression. 
The 
comments 
are 
classified 
according to predetermined criteria, such as 
hyperbole, 
euphemism, 
dysphemism, 
stigmatization, and animal association. We 
record supplementary observations to capture 
our perceptions and initial analyses of the data. 
The research data were collected from 
comments written in the Indonesian language on 
Facebook, specifically targeting those likely to 
provoke 
aggressive 
responses 
about 
controversial topics such as politics, religion, 
gender and social issues. The researcher's 
publicly accessible comments on their Facebook 
account 
were 
utilized, 
guaranteeing 
both 
relevance and ease of access. These comments 
were captured using a smartphone, and each 
screenshot was assigned a unique identifier to 
ensure the accuracy of the analysis by preserving 
the visual and contextual integrity. 
The data were obtained via comments 
posted on the researcher's Facebook account and 
further examined with descriptive methods. The 
process of data collection involved three primary 
methodologies: reviewing, documentation, and 
note-taking. 
We 
carefully 
analyzed 
the 
comments to identify occurrences of verbal 
aggression, capturing screenshots for record-
keeping purposes, and producing comprehensive 
notes on the nature and implications of the 
aggressive comments. The tools used included a 
smartphone for accessing Facebook, a laptop for 
data organizing, and notepad for note-taking.  
In conducting data analysis, we adhered to 
the methodologies of  Miles & Saldana, (2019), 
which involved the processes of data reduction, 
data display, and conclusion formulation and 
verification. During the process of data reduction, 
we compressed and focused on the most relevant 
data, categorizing it into categories according to 
the types of verbal aggression. Unrelated or less 
relevant details were eliminated to optimize the 
analysis 
process. 
Ultimately, 
we 
derived 
conclusions 
from 
the 
presented 
facts, 
consistently validating our discoveries to assure 
their accuracy and dependability. We cross-
verified our conclusions by comparing them 
with the initial observations and theoretical 
framework to ensure their consistency (Wodak 
& Meyer, 2011; Schiffrin et al.,2008). 
 
RESULTS AND DISCUSSION 
 
Research Results 
 
Through the conducted research, a total of 
15 instances of verbal aggression were identified. 
The 
identification 
of 
violence 
in 
Facebook social media comment discourse 
includes the use of hyperbole, euphemism, 
dysphemism, stigmatization, and association.  
The data obtained is derived from the outcomes 
of data analysis in the following manner.

  
Hyperbole 
the 
deliberate 
use 
of 
exaggerated language to create an effect, is a 
frequently employed rhetorical technique in 
online communication. Hyperbole is frequently 
used in Facebook comments to convey intense 
emotions or views, often leading to verbal 
aggression. The study aims to identify and 
analyse cases of hyperbole employed in verbal 
aggression within Facebook comments. 
 
(1). Kebanyakan bercermin pd kaca yg 
