towards the LGBT community. 
Euphemism is used in both posts to 
emphasize the negative characteristics or acts of 
the individual, thus heightening the verbal attack. 
Both excerpts exemplify how the use of 
euphemistic language may conceal underlying 
aggression and animosity, thereby becoming 
harsh criticisms more socially acceptable. 
Euphemisms enable commenters to tactfully 
address sensitive subjects and handle situations 
that may damage one's reputation, by taking into 
account the specific context and the audience's 
comprehension. The deliberate utilization of 
language 
emphasizes 
the 
significance 
of 
acknowledging and confronting euphemisms in 
online conversations to foster more constructive 
communication 
and 
diminish 
the 
subtle 
reinforcement of unfavorable stereotypes and 
prejudices. 
 
Dysphemism 
Dysphemism is the act of using strong or 
direct language to express a negative meaning, 
which can sometimes change how serious a 
remark appears. 
 
(6). Naik ... naik ke puncak gunung ... yg 
nikmat cuma pejabat dpt fasilitas terbaru trs 
Kasian rakyat diperas pajak gila2an hanya 
km syahwat penguasa ...(Climb... climb to 
the top of the mountain... (singing) the only 
thing that's good is that officials get the 
latest facilities, but it's a shame that the 
people are being extorted by crazy taxes, 
only you are lustful for the authorities...). 
 
The expression ""rakyat diperas"" (people are 
being 
clenched) 
utilizes 
dysphemism 
to 
denounce the government's tax practices. By 
employing the term ""diperas,"" the commentator 
amplifies the claim, implying a significant 
degree of exploitation of the people. 
 
(7) Tangkap penjarakan ..hams (harus) di 
penjara 5 tahun pmjara ..biar tidak diikuti 
ramai 
..mana 
... 
MUI 
.ini 
kerja ..MUI ..hanya tidurkah .. apa pura 
pura tak tau ..malu .. sebagai pemegang 
agama 
klu 
tidak 
bisa 
menjaga 
rakyatnya 
..mending 
berhenti 
saja. 
(Arrested, imprisoned..must be imprisoned 
for 5 years..so that the crowd doesn't 
follow..where is MUI. This is work.. (but) 
MUI..just sleeping..do you pretend you 
don't know..embarrassing..as a religious 
organization? can't take care of its people.. 
it's better to just stop..). 
 
The expression ""Tangkap, penjarakan"" 
(arrest and imprison) uses dysphemism to 
advocate for harsh punishment in response to a 
claimed offense. The commenter's use of blunt 
and harsh language amplifies the need for 
punishment, 
fostering 
an 
environment 
characterized by anger and hatred. 
 
(8). Dp sendiri kenapa mulutnya jg tak 
dijaga, menghujat lesty semua aja, apa iya 
mulutnya DP takda yg salah, sm aja DP jg 
kowar. (DP himself, why isn't his mouth

  
guarded, he's just blaspheming Lesty, is 
there nothing wrong with DP's mouth, but 
DP is also acting out.). 
 
The phrase ""mulutnya jg tak dijaga"" (her 
mouth is not controlled) used dysphemism to 
criticize the conduct of Indonesian musician 
Dewi Persik (DP). By employing the direct 
phrase 
""mulutnya 
jg 
tak 
dijaga,"" 
the 
commentator emphasizes the critique, implying 
that DP speaks irresponsibly and offensively. 
Dysphemism works to increase the negative 
characteristics or behaviors of the target. This 
direct and explicit language is used to critique 
and ridicule the subject, emphasizing perceived 
flaws 
in 
an 
excessively 
negative 
way. 
Commenters dehumanize their targets by using 
dysphemistic rhetoric. 
 
Stigmatization 
Stigmatization refers to the action of 
attaching a negative label or stigma to a person 
or group, typically with the aim of shaping 
others' perceptions and judgments of them. This 
practice can appear in either explicit or subtle 
forms, and its primary objective is to diminish 
the worth of the individual or group being 
attacked by linking them to bad characters or 
actions. 
 
(9). Seharusnya jd pribumi tuh yg sopan 
malu lg org pribumi ko kelakuan nya gtu 
malu"" in kmpung lo aj dasar manusia 
norak.. !!. (It's supposed to be a native who 
is polite and dignified. Native people 
behave so shamefully). 
 
The expression ""dasar manusia norak"" 
essentially uses stigmatization to censure and 
belittle an individual, categorizing them as 
lacking in sophistication and exhibiting shameful 
behavior. Within the given comment, this 
designation is explicitly directed towards a 
certain group known as ""pribumi"" (referring to 
native or indigenous people). The commentator 
aims to have a negative influence on the 
perception of the entire group by linking the 
insulting 
phrase 
""manusia 
norak"" 
with 
""pribumi."" The purpose of this stigmatization is 
to portray ""pribumi"" as fundamentally deficient 
in refinement and morality, thus lowering them 
to objects of mockery and reinforcing negative 
perceptions about indigenous people. This 
behavior not only diminishes the dignity of the 
person being directly spoken to, but also 
reinforces a wider societal prejudice against the 
""pribumi"" community as a whole, hence 
worsening their exclusion and social bias. 
 
10. Wajar Lah anak perempuan satu nya 
manja, dimana pun klo anak perempuan  
satu nya pasti manja dan kenak2kan itu 
fakta,  apalagi brojol ke dunia udah kaya 
raya. (It's normal for only daughters to be 
spoiled, wherever there is an only daughter, 
it's a fact that she's spoiled and spoiled, 
especially when you enter the world and are 
already very rich). 
 
The post uses stigmatization by adding an 
insulting label to the target, specifically referring 
to them as a ""only daughter."" The term ""manja"" 
(spoiled) is commonly used to highlight a 
perceived character issue linked to being an 
exclusively raised child, specifically an only 
daughter. The comment implies that this 
characteristic is an inevitable reality and 
strengthens this idea by connecting it to wealth, 
suggesting that being ""spoiled"" is a natural 
attribute of both being an only daughter and 
being wealthy. 
 
Extract 11. Kalau orang ga punya salah 
emang slow jawabnnya kaya si Abang,  nah 
kalau yang punya salah ngeles aja contoh 
para koruptor. (If someone doesn't make a 
mistake, he's slow to answer like Brother, 
but if someone makes a mistake, just 
change the subject like corruptor). 
 
The stigmatization in the context is clearly 
expressed. The term ""koruptor"" (corruptor) is a 
striking label that contains substantial negative 
connotations, indicating not only dishonesty but 
also moral and ethical corruption. The contrast 
of individuals who evade questions and corrupt 
individuals 
promotes 
a 
sweeping 
and 
unfavorable stereotype about those who avoid 
taking responsibility. 
Across all three excerpts, stigmatization 
serves to shape perceptions by associating the 
targets to negative characteristics, such as a lack 
of improvement, indulgent behavior, or moral 
corruption. This practice not only undermines 
the dignity of the targets involved but also 
strengthens 
reinforce 
social 
biases 
and

 
 
stereotypes. Gaining an in-depth understanding 
of these dynamics is essential in order to 
effectively tackle the negative effects of 
stigmatization in online discussions and foster a 
culture 
of 
respectful 
and 
inclusive 
communication. 
  
 
Association 
Association, in the context of verbal 
aggression, involves the act of relating a person 
to an animal with the intention of degrading, 
insulting, or lowering their worth. This language 
employs metaphors or analogies that establish 
connections 
between 
perceived 
negative 
attributes of animals and the individual being 
criticized. The main purpose of such associations 
is to strip the person of their dignity and 
humanity, therefore reinforcing the verbal 
assault and creating damaging stereotypes. 
 
12. Berati kmaren gua ktmu emak yg 
badannya ke ikan dugong dengan sinis 
menatap saya itu termasuk kekerasan 
seksual?? Aku kotooooor. (Does that mean 
that yesterday I met mothers whose bodies 
were 
like 
dugong 
fish 
and 
looked 
sarcastically at me, that was sexual 
violence?? I was dirty). 
 
The expression ""badannya ke ikan dugong"" 
(body like a dugong) exemplifies body shaming, 
where the individual's physical appearance is 
mocked by relating them to a dugong, a large 
marine mammal commonly regarded as clumsy. 
This comparison used sarcasm and vulgar words 
to 
ridicule 
and 
degrade 
the 
person, 
demonstrating a contemptuous attitude. 
 
13. Ojo ngapusi lho pak, ntar kalo kualat 
jadi monyet. Eh jambu monyet maksudnya. 
(Don't lie to me sir, I'll be able to turn into a 
monkey. I mean a cashew). 
 
This term uses the concept of ""kualat,"" an 
Indonesian term signifies a curse or bad karma 
that affect someone who has committed a 
wrongful actions. The statement implies that if 
the person lies, they will be cursed to turn into a 
monkey. The speaker corrects their prior 
statement by using ""jambu monyet,"" which is the 
Indonesian term for cashew. This clarification is 
presumably given in a sarcastic or comical tone, 
implying that the initial comment was too 
insulting or that the speaker is mocking the 
seriousness of the curse. 
 
14. Paling muak kalo ada orang yg bilang 
'gue pribumi' emang nya ada orang yg tiba 
keluar dari tanah? Smua manusia itu 
pendatang & keturunan nya campuran, ga 
ada yg bener bisa jamin 100% orang 
pribumi, kalo yg pribumi asli mungkin 
'orang utan. (Most annoyed when someone 
says 'I'm native.' Is there anyone who 
suddenly emerges from the ground? All 
humans are immigrants & their lineage is 
mixed, no one can really guarantee 100% 
being native, if there's a true native maybe 
it's an 'orangutan). 
 
The phrase ""pribumi asli mungkin 'orang 
utan'"" (real natives are probably orangutans) 
devalues indigenous people by drawing a 
comparison between them and orangutans, 
implying that their identity is equivalent to that 
of an animal. This degrading analogy diminishes 
the sense of self and worth of the ""pribumi"" 
(indigenous people). 
 
15. Lah cewenya mirip babi. (Wah, she 
looks like a pig). 
 
The expression ""cewenya mirip babi"" is a 
straightforward insult that directly compares a 
woman's appearance to that of a pig, with the 
intention 
of 
demeaning 
her 
physical 
attractiveness. This association use vulgar 
language and sarcasm to intensify the insult, so 
reinforcing the practice of criticizing people's 
bodies 
and 
encouraging 
an 
aggressive 
atmosphere. 
These extracts employ the association with 
animals as a means of verbal aggression to 
degrade and offend others. The commenters 
diminish the dignity and humanity of their 
targets by likening them to animals with bad 
features. These derogatory comparisons sustain 
damaging 
generalizations, 
bolster 
the 
stigmatization of physical appearance, and foster 
an antagonistic atmosphere for communication. 
 
Discussion 
 
The themes encompassed in this list are 
Stigmatization, and Association. Each of these

  
elements has a unique function in determining 
the character and influence of aggressive online 
communication. Acquiring a comprehensive 
understanding of these themes is essential in 
order to formulate effective strategies aimed at 
reducing the negative consequences of verbal 
and 
fostering 
healthier 
communication practices on the internet. 
The presence of hyperbole in the analysed 
Facebook posts serves as a typical strategy in 
cyberbullying, where exaggerated language is 
used to increase the emotional effect and 
intensify conflict. By presenting criticisms in 
extreme terms, hyperbole in these remarks 
diminishes 
the 
chance 
for 
sympathetic 
communication. This supports Ignat & Vogel 
(2022) finding that the use of exaggerated 
language in cyberbullying hinders productive 
conversation and promotes a hostile atmosphere. 
Brantly (2020) provides additional evidence for 
this claim by demonstrating how the use of 
hyperbole in cyber conflict can intensify 
tensions and impede the process of finding a 
solution, as exaggerated threats and reactions 
overshadow rational discussions. 
Euphemisms employed in social media aim 
to mitigate the impact of language, creating 
more agreeable communication and minimizing 
the possibility of conflict. This study emphasizes 
the significance of euphemism in online 
interactions, where the use of harsh language can 
quickly intensify conflicts and elicit strong 
emotional responses. Waljinaha et al. (2020) 
emphasizes the utilization of euphemisms to 
reduce the impact of words that could be 
perceived to be harsh or offensive. They 
classified euphemism into figurative expressions, 
circumlocution, hyperbole, and colloquial forms 
in 
order 
to 
facilitate 
more 
agreeable 
communication. While they emphasize the 
significance 
of 
euphemism 
in 
upholding 
politeness and preventing offense, our study also 
underscores 
how 
euphemisms 
can 
still 
effectively convey intense negative sentiments. 
As an example, the phrase ""sekumpulan preman 
diwadahi"" subtly criticizes the structuring of a 
collective referred to as ""thugs,"" insinuating 
possible illicit activities without explicitly 
mentioning them. The statement ""jejak LGBT 
itu kalau di telusuri awalnya dari trauma masa 
kecil"" (the origins of LGBT can be traced back 
to childhood trauma) insinuates that being 
LGBT is a consequence of adverse encounters, 
presenting the matter in a manner that casts 
doubt on the authenticity of LGBT identities 
without 
employing 
explicitly 
offensive 
terminology. Metaphorical language is used to 
subtly express criticism, as evidenced by a study 
on metaphorical euphemism in comments on 
President 
Joko 
Widodo's 
Facebook 
(Haryanto et al., 2023). Similarly, we have found 
that euphemisms such as ""pembohongan dan 
pembodohan publik"" use metaphorical elements 
to conceal explicit allegations of deceit and 
manipulation. 
The use of dysphemism in the Facebook 
is 
evident 
through 
aggressive, 
straightforward language aimed at intensify 
negative meanings and emphasizing perceived 
flaws. The phrase ""rakyat diperas"" (people are 
being clenched) is a critical commentary on the 
government's 
taxation 
procedure, 
implying 
exploitation. Similarly, ""Tangkap, penjarakan"" 
(arrest and imprison) promotes the idea of 
extreme punishment, intensifying the sense of 
urgency and anger in the critique. The 
expression ""mulutnya jg tak dijaga"" (her mouth 
is not controlled) directly criticizes the target's 
manner of speech, suggesting recklessness and 
offensiveness. Winter-Froemel (2017) stated that 
dysphemisms serve several pragmatic functions. 
They 
emphasize 
societal 
taboos 
and 
communicate a sense of urgency and severity, as 
evident 
in 
extracts. 
 
Additionally, 
these 
comments provoke   strong emotional reactions, 
fostering a more intense response from the 
audience. Olimat (2020) highlights the strategic 
use of dysphemism by political figures such as 
Donald Trump to shape public opinion, justify 
their positions, and attack opponents. 
Hiskes 
(2019) 
presents 
a 
valuable 
framework for understanding the complexity of 
stigmatization by highlighting that it involves 
the identification and perception of specific 
qualities as undesirable, thus diminishing the 
target to a damaged state. This process impacts 
social identity by categorizing individuals as 
fundamentally distinct and less desirable. This 
concept is clearly observable in the comments 
examined, where stigmatizing language is 
employed 
to 
marginalize 
individuals 
by 
associating 
them 
with 
unfavorable 
characteristics. Terms such as ""manusia norak,"" 
""manja,"" and ""koruptor"" are used to stigmatize 
indigenous individuals, only daughters, and 
those 
who 
avoid 
taking 
responsibility,

 
 
respectively. These labels undermine the dignity 
of individuals and promote social biases, leading 
to social exclusion and prejudice. This study 
emphasizes the utilization of terminology to 
sustain stereotypes and marginalize individuals. 
Li et al. (2018) explores the use of stigmatizing 
language to express negative attitudes towards 
depression, 
employing 
terms 
that 
imply 
unpredictability, weakness, or the invalidity of 
the illness. Both studies employ linguistic 
analysis to identify and comprehend the patterns 
of stigmatizing language. Li et al. (2018)utilize 
computational models to identify instances of 
depression stigma in Weibo posts. The linguistic 
features examined, such as the utilization of 
negative emotion words, cognitive processes, 
and social processes, are present in both studies, 
emphasizing the significance of language in 
sustaining stigma. 
Association, in the context of verbal 
aggression, refers to the deliberate act of 
connecting a person to an animal in order to 
demean, insult, or diminish their value. This 
language utilizes metaphors or analogies to 
establish 
correlations 
between 
perceived 
negative characteristics of animals and the 
person being criticized. The primary objective of 
such associations is to deprive individuals of 
their dignity and humanity, intensifying the 
verbal attack and creating damaging stereotypes. 
Comparing people to animals is a common 
method of dehumanization, reducing their 
perceived humanity and worth (Ligman et al., 
2024). The use of association emphasizes the 
wider social consequences and inherent potential 
for negative impacts in these verbal attacks 
(Wahlström et al., 2021). 
 
CONCLUSIONS 
 
This study has examined five main themes 
Stigmatization, and Association that characterize 
in 
Facebook 
in 
Indonesian social media. These themes play 
specific roles in shaping the character and 
influence of aggressive online interaction. The 
study's 
findings 
highlight 
the 
complex 
interaction of these rhetorical techniques in 
creating 
and 
sustaining 
harmful stereotypes. Addressing these problems 
requires a 
comprehensive strategy, which 
involves 
increasing 
awareness 
about 
the 
consequences of such language, encouraging 
respectful 
communication, 
and 
enforcing 
policies to decrease verbal aggression online. By 
promoting a more inclusive and respectful 
digital space, we can reduce the negative 
impacts of verbal aggression and support 
healthier communications on social media.","This study investigates the phenomenon of verbal aggression in posts on social media platforms, particularly Facebook, in Indonesian language. The research applied a qualitative descriptive methodology to explore the ways in which verbal aggressiveness manifests in user conversations within a specific linguistic and cultural specific context. The analysis, based on Pierre Bourdieu's Symbolic Violence theory, aims to identify several types and interpretations of verbal aggression, including hyperbole, euphemism, dysphemism, stigmatization, and association. The results indicate that Indonesian Facebook users often employ these linguistic tactics to express aggression in a subtle or explicit manner. This study not only classifies the various forms of verbal aggressiveness commonly found in Indonesian Facebook conversations, but also analyzes the social and cultural elements that shape these interactions. The study emphasizes the significance of comprehending cultural subtleties in verbal aggression in digital communication, which could be advantageous in formulating improved social media communication rules and cultivating a more courteous online interaction environment."
"CONTENT OF ECOLOGICAL INTELLIGENCE IN INDONESIAN 
LANGUAGE TEACHING MATERIALS IN THEMATIC TEXTBOOKS 
IN PRIMARY SCHOOLS  
Sobri, Imam Safi’i, Sri Mulyani, Lili Wahdini  
1 Universitas Sultan Ageng Tirtayasa 
2, 3 Universitas Muhammadiyah Prof. Dr. Hamka 
4 Universitas Tama Jagarakarsa 
1 Jl. Ciwaru Raya, Cipare, Kec. Serang, Kota Serang, Banten 
2,3 Jl. Limau II No.2, Kramat Pela, Kec. Kebayoran Baru, Daerah Khusus Ibukota Jakarta 
1 Jl. TB Simatupang No.152, Tanjung Barat, Kec. Jagakarsa, Kota Jakarta Selatan, Daerah Khusus Ibukota Jakarta 
 
