Discussion 
 
Based on the findings above, it can be seen 
that there are many ecological aspects in 
Indonesian 
language 
teaching 
subjects 
in 
thematic books for class VI elementary school, 
but they are still not very diverse. The ecological 
aspects contained in the textbook are related to 
two basic themes, namely animals and plants. If 
referring to the components regarding ecological 
aspects expressed by  BPS (2013) still very 
minimal. Components mentioned by BPS (2013) 
are very complex, namely in the form of housing 
facilities, use of technology, use of water, use of 
transportation, 
waste 
management, 
and 
participation in environmental maintenance. 
The lack of ecological aspect components 
contained in Indonesian language teaching 
materials in thematic books for sixth grade 
elementary school students is certainly not in 
line with the strategic role of textbooks, that 
teaching materials or school textbooks are one of 
the main sources of the teaching and learning 
process in the education system (Seddighi et al., 
2021; Kinanti & Sudirman, 2017). Because it is 
the main source of learning, the material 
component of ecology must certainly cover a 
variety of topics. The diversity of topics in 
textbooks will provide students with diverse 
knowledge. In this way, students' knowledge will 
increase. The amount of knowledge will 
contribute to increasing students' cognitive 
skills. Cognitive aspects influence student 
learning outcomes (Ulfah & Arifudin, 2021). 
Cognitive load also has a significant relationship 
to student learning outcomes (Hsu, 2021). The 
use of learning media, in this case, related to the 
choice of teaching materials related to ecology, 
will influence understanding and knowledge, 
even students' attitudes about ecology. The use 
of media also influences learning outcomes 
(Haryana et al., 2022). 
When compared with several previous 
studies, especially related to the appropriateness 
of textbooks, the findings regarding the minimal 
diversity of ecological aspects in thematic 
textbooks for sixth grade elementary school 
are 
in 
line 
the 
results 
(Hendrawanto & Mulyani, 2017) related to 
textbook quality. According to him, the level of 
suitability of textbooks in terms of language and 
content is not yet optimal. This is different from 
the results of research from (Listeani et al., 
2021) that in terms of the electronic school 
textbook (BSE) evaluation instrument it has met 
the eligibility standards. that book I, published 
by the non-Ministry of Education and Culture, 
meets the elements of appropriateness or good 
(Purnanto 
& 
Mustadi, 
2016). 
Likewise, 
according to (Aliyansyah et al., 2021) the 
thematic book for elementary school with the 
theme Loving Plants and Animals has met the

 
 
requirements, both in terms of spiritual-social 
dimensions and skills. 
Furthermore, regarding the diversity of 
ecological aspects contained in Indonesian 
thematic books for elementary school class VI. 
Conveying information to other people regarding 
environmental issues can be a way to share 
knowledge about an important part of living. 
Understanding the means of life can direct a 
person to act more wisely in making use of life. 
This is because good living facilities will have 
implications for comfort, peace and tranquillity. 
The means of life found in thematic textbooks 
for elementary school students are broadly 
divided into two categories, namely plants and 
animals. This category is still very minimal, 
considering that ecological aspects are very 
complex and need to be informed to students so 
that 
they 
have 
comprehensive 
sensitivity. For example, related to plants and 
animals, they can continue with their care. For 
example, it is related to the issue of using 
pesticides to fertilize plants, but actually, it has 
negative consequences for the environment. 
Increasing knowledge of the impacts of 
pesticides on soil ecological communities is 
fundamental to a comprehensive understanding 
of 
functional 
changes 
in 
the 
global 
agroecosystem industry (Qin et al., 2023). We 
can also add information about plants, that in 
essence plants are capable of sensing sound and 
promise not only the benefits of good treatment 
in agriculture but also the possibility of 
ecological relevance (Demey et al., 2023). 
Furthermore, the findings on ecological 
aspects regarding involvement in environmental 
saving activities also do not cover issues or 
problems comprehensively. The issues raised 
still emphasize how to reproduce and care for 
animals and plants. Ecological aspects can be 
linked to life problems in urban communities. 
For example, it is related to the impact of urban 
planning that does not pay attention to the 
environment. Industrial development, and use of 
transportation. In building cities, attention needs 
to be paid to improving metabolic networks 
synergistically, such as strengthening local 
resource reserves, increasing the efficiency of 
utilization of dominant industries and promoting 
medicine and treatment (Li et al., 2023). 
Apart from that, the ecological aspects 
contained in the thematic book Unstuck for sixth 
grade elementary school students are also not 
linked to the wider environment. For example, 
related to clean water sources, rivers and also 
water channels. Talking about rivers, for 
example, there has been no emphasis that side 
channels in large rivers in flood plains have 
various important ecological roles, especially in 
areas where habitat conditions have been 
degraded or reduced (Bouska et al., 2023). 
Managing and maintaining the balance of 
ecosystem services is a key challenge for 
ensuring sustainable social-ecological systems 
(Shen et al., 2023). In learning Indonesian, 
various information regarding ecological aspects 
can become material or sources for writing. 
Access to writing resources impacts writing test 
task performance (Pusey & Butler, 2023). Thus, 
providing teaching materials with diverse 
ecological content will be able to increase 
students' ecological intelligence. In writing 
activities about waste management, for example, 
intelligence 
has 
a 
very 
close 
relationship 
waste 
sorting 
activities 
(Wahdah et al., 2020). 
This 
study 
revealed 
that 
competence is one of the competencies that is 
increasingly emphasized in textbooks, especially 
at the elementary and secondary education 
levels. From the content analysis of the 
textbooks used in this study, it can be seen that 
the books have begun to integrate important 
concepts related to environmental awareness. 
However, the results of the study indicate 
that despite efforts to include ecological content, 
the quality and depth of the material still vary. 
Some textbooks only present basic information 
without providing space for students to develop 
critical skills in understanding and addressing 
ecological problems. This indicates the need for 
revision and improvement in the preparation of 
textbooks so that they not only convey 
information but also equip students with critical 
thinking skills in an ecological context. 
In addition, another important finding is the 
limitation in the use of an interdisciplinary 
approach. Most textbooks still separate ecology 
lessons from other subjects, whereas a more 
holistic and integrative approach can provide a 
deeper understanding of the relationship between 
humans and the environment. For example, 
linking 
ecology 
lessons 
social 
and 
economic studies can help students understand 
the broader implications of environmental 
issues.

  
The study also found that textbooks that 
include real-life stories or cases about local 
environmental issues tend to be more effective in 
building students’ ecological skills. This is due 
to the relevance and closeness of the topics 
discussed to students’ daily experiences, which 
encourages them to be more concerned and 
involved in environmental issues. 
Overall, 
this 
study 
emphasizes 
the 
importance 
of 
improving 
the 
quality 
of 
ecological materials in textbooks and developing 
more effective teaching methods to build 
ecological skills. Interdisciplinary and contextual 
approaches are key to maximizing the potential 
of ecological education contained in textbooks. 
 
CONCLUSIONS 
 
The 
aspects 
contained 
in 
Indonesian language teaching materials in 
thematic texts for sixth grade elementary school 
students have been developed, but they do not 
yet include aspects as diverse as the diversity of 
ecological intelligence in the National Statistical 
Agency. The ecological aspect that has been 
developed only includes one aspect, namely 
participation in environmental maintenance. This 
ecological aspect has only been developed in 
two ways, namely conveying information to 
other people regarding environmental problems 
and involvement in activities to save the 
environment. However, these two aspects have 
not been elaborated into various topics. 
In terms of context or scope of research, 
this research has not yet focused on objects in 
the form of thematic textbooks for elementary 
school students as a whole. New research has 
determined a thematic book intended for sixth 
grade elementary school students. Therefore data 
is still very limited. Further research remains 
important and interesting to carry out to obtain a 
more comprehensive picture dealing with 
various aspects of ecology contained in the 
lesson textbook. In this way, information about 
the suitability and readiness of textbooks to 
support the development of students' ecological 
skills can continue to be improved.","This study aims to explore the ecological content contained in Indonesian teaching materials in thematic textbooks for grade VI primary school students. The method used is content analysis. The data source in this study is Indonesian teaching materials contained in thematic textbooks intended for grade VI students. The textbooks analyzed were purposefully selected, namely textbooks published by the Ministry of Education and Culture (2018). Data were collected through a document study of the content of the textbooks, where each topic and subtopic related to ecology was identified and categorized based on the guidelines that had been prepared. The collected data were analyzed using qualitative descriptive analysis techniques. The process of data analysis involves the stages of coding data, categorizing data, and analyzing it to see the frequency of occurrence and distribution of ecological content in textbooks. The results showed that Indonesian teaching materials in thematic textbooks contain various aspects of ecology. The ecological aspects presented include types of plants and animals, the influence of geographical conditions on life, consumption of a healthy diet for the body, economic potential in terms of natural resources, the benefits of a healthy environment for the health of the body, and how to breed living things. The results of this study can be used as material for evaluating the feasibility of textbook content."
