Discussion 
 
The inadequate level of natural disaster 
mitigation literacy in Indonesia is a significant 
challenge for disaster preparedness and response 
efforts in Indonesia. Indonesia's geographical 
location on tectonic plates makes Indonesia very 
vulnerable to various natural disasters such as 
earthquakes, floods, landslides, tsunamis, and 
others (Martono et al., 2019). Despite these risks, 
research shows that disaster mitigation literacy 
among adolescents (students) is still relatively 
low, 
which 
has 
an 
impact 
on 
preparedness (Meliana et al., 2020). Disaster 
literacy, defined as the ability to acquire, 
understand, and utilize disaster information for 
informed 
decision-making 
in 
mitigation, 
preparedness, emergency response, and recovery, 
is critical, but still lacking among certain 
communities (Zhang et al., 2021). 
This is also in accordance with the reality in 
the field. Based on the results of the 
questionnaire shared, children do not know about 
natural disaster mitigation. In fact, in the 
student's area, there has been a natural disaster. 
This condition is also supported by the results of 
interviews with teachers who stated that the 
natural disaster mitigation literacy program has 
never been carried out in schools. Also, the low 
availability of literacy materials for natural 
disaster mitigation. 
In fact, disaster preparedness education 
must start early to ensure that children are 
equipped with the necessary knowledge to 
protect themselves (Dewi et al., 2024; Mandal et 
al., 2023). Thus, disaster mitigation literacy 
plays an important role in reducing disaster risk 
by increasing awareness, capacity building, and 
to 
address 
potential 
threats 
(Damayani 
et 
al., 
2022; Surwandono 
& 
Muhammad, 2023). Efforts to increase disaster 
literacy aim to increase students' awareness of 
potential disasters and equip them with the 
knowledge needed to prepare and respond 
effectively (Saminan, 2024). 
This study is based on the development of 
material based on empirical data from student 
questionnaire data and teacher interviews which 
show that disaster mitigation literacy among 
students is still low. Also, the readiness of 
schools and students to utilize digital media. 
These results underscore the importance of 
enrichment materials specifically designed to 
increase disaster awareness and preparedness, by 
adjusting students' preferences for picture 
reading and video-integrated interactive digital 
books. 
Seeing this reality, the preparation of 
enrichment materials in increasing awareness of 
disasters for students is important (Meliana et al., 
2020). Natural disaster mitigation is an important 
effort to be made to reduce the risk and impact of 
disasters that can occur, especially in vulnerable 
areas such as Indonesia which is on the Pacific 
Ring of Fire (Rahma, 2018). In the context of 
natural disaster mitigation literacy, approaches 
that can be taken include the development of 
various educational media, such as animated 
videos, games, and interactive multimedia, 
which aim to engage students effectively 
(Makrifah & Sudarmilah, 2019). This is in line 
with the questionnaire data that 90.4% of 
students like picture reading as exposed in 
Figure 2 and 79.8% of students like video-
integrated digital books as described in Figure 3.  
For this reason, this study introduces the 
use of book creators as a versatile digital media 
to develop literacy materials for natural disaster 
mitigation. It includes the use of multimedia 
elements such as images, videos, and audio to 
create interactive scenarios that enhance the 
student learning experience. This approach offers 
a more engaging and easy-to-understand method 
of conveying complex information about natural 
disaster mitigation.

  
Book creator as a versatile digital media can 
be used to create interactive digital books that 
combine multimedia elements, such as images, 
videos, and audio that can be used in the 
preparation of natural disaster mitigation literacy 
materials. This is because book creators provide 
a platform to create interactive scenarios that 
enhance the learning experience through various 
multimedia elements, such as simulation videos 
when disasters occur, evacuation diagrams, and 
audio warnings (Bookcreator, 2024). Digital 
books with multimedia content, including images, 
audio, and video, have been shown to facilitate a 
deeper understanding of learning materials 
(Sihombing et al., 2024).  
By using images, videos, and audio, book 
creators can create natural disaster mitigation 
literacy materials that are more interesting and 
easier to understand. This multimedia element 
helps convey complex information about natural 
disaster mitigation in a way that is more 
accessible to students. The use of multimedia in 
learning can improve students' understanding of 
disaster mitigation in a more visual and 
interactive way (Juhadi et al., 2021). Simulation 
videos help students engage in realistic scenarios, 
facilitating 
the 
practical 
application 
of 
knowledge (Tabuenca et al., 2021).  
Thus, book creators offer many advantages 
in improving natural disaster mitigation literacy 
through the integration of video, images, and text. 
In the realm of disaster mitigation literacy, the 
integration of multimedia elements such as 
videos, images, and texts play an important role 
in improving student understanding. Videos 
provide 
dynamic 
visualizations 
that 
help 
understand before a disaster, during a disaster, 
after a disaster, and the impact of a disaster. 
Images 
contribute 
to 
creating 
a 
clear 
representation of disaster mitigation strategies, 
while text provides detailed explanations to 
complement the visual and auditory components 
(Abdulrahaman et al., 2020). By combining 
these multimedia elements, learning becomes 
more interesting, interactive, and effective in 
increasing students' understanding of the concept 
of natural disaster mitigation (Arifina et al.,  
2021). 
Furthermore, the results of the study show 
that the natural disaster mitigation literacy 
teaching materials developed have very high 
material feasibility in three main aspects: content 
(87.5%), presentation (95%), and language 
(100%). This validation shows that the material 
prepared is very effective, engaging, and easy to 
understand for students, and meets the quality 
standards required in the context of disaster 
education. 
Also, 
the 
average 
percentage of the feasibility of the design of the 
developed teaching materials is 86.90 and is in 
the very good category. The quality of teaching 
materials, which includes aspects such as 
readability, attractiveness, and relevance, can 
significantly impact student motivation and 
learning outcomes. Likewise, the results of the 
effectiveness test are in the good category with 
an average achievement of 72.07. 
The effectiveness test carried out is also 
supported by the responses of students and 
teachers to the teaching materials developed. The 
response of students was 83.75% and the teacher 
84.17% were each at a positive response. 
Positive responses from teachers and students in 
the effectiveness test of teaching materials play a 
crucial role as evaluative data. This data is used 
to understand the advantages and disadvantages 
of teaching materials and ensure that they are in 
line with user needs before being implemented 
more broadly. This feedback also helps in 
refining teaching materials to be more effective 
and well accepted by all parties involved in the 
learning process (Arrajiv et al., 2023; Kurniawan 
& Furqon, 2023). 
The 
of 
book creators has become a focal point in 
modern 
education 
to 
students' 
understanding and preparedness in dealing with 
disasters. Integrating digital learning tools into 
natural disaster mitigation literacy materials has 
been recognized as a contemporary approach to 
creating interactive and engaging content (Sari,, 
2022). Disaster literacy includes the knowledge 
and skills individuals need to be resilient in the 
face 
of 
disasters, 
including 
preparedness, 
mitigation, response, and recovery (Çallşkan & 
Üner, 2021). Effective 
disaster mitigation 
education requires the development of specific 
learning content to equip students with essential 
and 
understanding 
of 
disasters and preparedness measures (Putra et al., 
2024).

 
 
CONCLUSIONS 
 
This study shows that the literacy level of 
natural disaster mitigation among students in 
Indonesia is still low even though the country is 
very vulnerable to various natural disasters. The 
study found that many students do not have basic 
knowledge about natural disaster mitigation, 
even though they live in disaster-prone areas. 
The results of questionnaires and interviews with 
teachers revealed that natural disaster mitigation 
literacy programs are rare, if not ever, carried out 
in schools. This underscores the importance of 
disaster preparedness education early on to 
ensure that children are equipped with the 
necessary knowledge to protect themselves. 
The use of book creators as interactive 
digital media in the development of natural 
disaster mitigation literacy materials has proven 
to 
be 
effective 
in 
improving 
student 
understanding. Multimedia elements such as 
images, videos, and audio integrated in digital 
books make learning materials more interesting 
and easier to understand. The validation of the 
material shows that the quality of the content, 
presentation, and language in this teaching 
material is very high, with a feasibility score that 
shows the effectiveness and attractiveness of the 
learning media. This study shows that the 
development of teaching materials that utilize 
digital technology and multimedia elements can 
increase natural disaster mitigation literacy 
among students so that they are more prepared 
and responsive in facing potential disasters in the 
future. 
Overall, the results of this study indicate 
that the implementation of interactive digital 
media such as book creators in disaster 
mitigation literacy education has great potential. 
This not only improves student understanding 
and engagement, but also ensures that the 
material delivered is in line with educational 
quality standards. Thus, the development and 
application of multimedia-based digital teaching 
materials is a strategic step in increasing literacy 
in natural disaster mitigation and disaster 
preparedness.","This research aims to develop teaching materials for natural disaster mitigation literacy with the help of book creators for junior high school students. The method used is R&D with a 4D model (define, design, develop, disseminate). The population of this study is students of SMP Pasundan 3 Bandung with a sample of class VIII A of 29 people. The data analysis techniques used are qualitative descriptive and quantitative descriptive. In the effectiveness test of teaching materials, the data analysis used was a paired sample t-test. The results of the study show that based on the analysis of the need for the availability of teaching materials, natural disaster mitigation literacy is still limited and 90% of students do not know about natural disaster mitigation. At the design stage, natural disaster mitigation media and content are designed to be attractive and easy to understand by combining images and videos in each chapter. At the development stage, the validation of material and media experts was 94.17% and 86.90% which were in the valid category. The effectiveness test showed an increase in student understanding to 72.07 after the posttest with a paired test until a t test of p= 0.000 < 0.05. It can be concluded that innovative digital teaching materials are important in improving students' preparedness for natural disasters."
