Direct Speech Act  
Direct speech act is speech act that matches 
the mode and function of the speech. Direct 
speech act in the expression of magical power 
contains imperative mode and obligative mode. 
Imperative 
used 
to 
order, 
appeal,

 
 
prohibition, and exlamation. While, obligative 
mode used to require.  
 
Imperative Mode 
An order is called direct if the order is 
conveyed in a sentence with an imperative 
mode, namely a sentence that is formed to ask 
for a response in the form of an act and is 
marked with command expressions such as the 
ending '-lah' (Alwi, et al in Sholiha et al., 2020) . 
Imperative mode is a mode that states order, 
prohibition or prevention (Firman et al., 2016). 
Imperative mode in the expression of magical 
power contains command that is used to give 
order, prohibit, and reinforce motivation. 
